<HEADLINE> Clinton Speaks of His First Impression on China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Here in this ancient capital, China
seems very young to me tonight, blessed with both a proud history
and the promise of tomorrow, U.S. President bill Clinton said here
this evening.
</P>
<P>
"Over 1,000 years ago, Xi'an was perhaps the most open and
culturally advanced city in the entire world," the U.S. president
said to thousands of local people who gave him a "magnificant
welcome" as he said.
</P>
<P>
"I look forward to learning more about China's great
contributions to the store of human knowledge, from medicine and
printing to mathematics and astronomy -- discoveries on which so
much of the whole world's progress is based," he said.
</P>
<P>
"And I want to see more of the new nation you are building on a
scale even the emperors could not have foreseen," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived here earlier this evening for a nine-day state
visit at the invitation of Chinese President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
The visit, a return to the state visit by his Chinese
counterpart Jiang Zemin last October, marks a major event in the
Sino-U.S. relations, observers here said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is accompanied by his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton,
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Secretary of Treasury
Robert Rubin, and other senior U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an is the first leg of his nine-day tour of China and he is
scheduled to visit Beijing, Shanghai, Guilin and Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
