<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Argentina Sign Accord on Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
signed Thursday with his visiting Argentine counterpart, Carlos
Menem, an agreement on the basic principles of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The document, inked after their talks in the Kremlin, calls for
closer contacts at different levels between the two countries,
including annual consultations between their foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also encourages broadening exchanges between the
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), and the Rio Group and
the South American Common Market.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the two countries also signed several accords on
air traffic, cooperation between interior ministries, cultural and
educational exchanges and mutual protection of investments.
</P>
<P>
Menem arrived here Wednesday on a state visit. Before finishing
his Russia trip and fly Sunday to his next destination, the
Ukrainian capital of Kiev, he is scheduled to visit St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
Argentina is one of Russia's major trading partners in South
America. Annual trade between the two countries has leaped from
140 million U.S. dollars to 225 million dollars in recent years,
but it still falls short of the two governments' expectation of 3
billion dollars, the peak volume in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Fuel, lubricants, power and mining equipment, aviation
technology and road-paving machinery are Russia's main exports to
Argentina, while Argentina's main exports to Russia are food
products such as vegetable oil, meat and fruits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
