<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Rating Affirmed At "A+:" IBCA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Fitch IBCA, the international
rating agency, affirmed Thursday its "A+" Long-term foreign
currency rating for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The agency also affirmed its rating of "F1+" for short-term
issues and of "AA+" for sovereign issues in Hong Kong dollars.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the above affirmation, the rating agency said in a
statement, "The fiscal package announced by the Hong Kong
government on 22 June is a small but welcome contribution to the
process of restoring confidence in the economy."
</P>
<P>
The measures in total have been cost by the authorities at HKD
32 bn (2.3 percent of GDP) and will produce a deficit of at least
HKD 21 bn, it adds.
</P>
<P>
The agency believed this is clearly unusual for a society
acclimated to continuing surpluses but, seen in the light of an
accumulated fiscal surplus of some HKD 450 bn, is hardly fiscal
recklessness.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, IBCA stated the decision to suspend government land
sales for nine months against the background of a fall in property
prices of about 40 percent since the peak last year can be
regarded as common sense, rather than a massive departure from
Hong Kong's traditional non-interventionist approach.
</P>
<P>
The agency argued the major concern remains the fixed link to
the U.S. dollar and Hong Kong's commitment to the automatic
currency board mechanism which underpins this.
</P>
<P>
However, IBCA believed the behavior of the authorities over the
past year gives no reason to doubt this commitment, and the same
is true of the Chinese authorities.
</P>
<P>
Between them, the agency said, they have enough foreign
exchange reserves to repel all but the most massive of speculative
attacks. Furthermore, the agency cannot see what advantage could
be gained by permitting the link to break. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
