<HEADLINE> Switzerland Aids Nepal in Health Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss government has agreed
to grant an assistance of 2.95 million Swiss francs (about 2
million U.S. dollars) to Nepal for the implementation of the
second-phase rural health development project, the Nepali RSS news
agency said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss government has financed the first phase of the
"primary health care, mother and child health/family planning
project" in Dolakha and Ramechhap districts of central Nepal since
1992.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the project runs for four years to the year
2001, the official RSS said.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to improve access to comprehensive health
services at the local level and enhance health conditions in the
community, it added.
</P>
<P>
Inadequate health facilities, in particular the shortage of
medicine and doctors, are among the major problems facing the
rural areas of the Himalayan kingdom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
