<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Three-Year ESAF Credit for Tajikistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) Thursday announced the approval of a three-year credit for
Tajikistan under the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility,
equivalent to about 128 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The credit is provided in support of the government's 1998-2001
economic program. The first annual loan is equivalent to about 48
million dollars and is divided into two equal semiannual
installments, the first of which is available immediately.
</P>
<P>
The government's medium-term strategy is based on export-led
growth, building on a liberal foreign trade and investment regime.
The program envisions real GDP growth of 4 to 4.5 percent a year
from 1999 through 2001. In the first year of the program, GDP
growth is targeted at 3.4 percent in 1998, inflation at 16.8
percent, and the external current account deficit at 5.0 percent
of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Tajikistan joined the IMF in April 1993. Its quota in the IMF
is about 80 million dollars and its outstanding use of the IMF
financing currently totals about 40 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
