<HEADLINE> U.S President Clinton Arrives in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the ceremony, Xi'an Mayor Feng Xuchu presented President
Clinton with a "golden key" as a symbol of opening the gate of the
ancient city.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton received the "golden key" with delight, and
expressed his thanks.
</P>
<P>
Then, President and Mrs. Clinton watched song and dance items
performed by young girls dressed in Tang Dynasty costumes as maids
of honor.
</P>
<P>
Governor Cheng Andong and Mayor Feng Xuchu explained the
backgrounds of the city to the presidential couple.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, Mayor Feng gave a warm-welcome speech.
</P>
<P>
In response, President Clinton spoke highly of the city's long
history of civilization.
</P>
<P>
"Here in this ancient capital, China seems very young to me
tonight, blessed with both a proud history and the promise of
tomorrow," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I look forward to learning more about China's great
contributions to the store of human knowledge," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We Americans admire your accomplishments, your
economy, your hard work, creativity, and vision."
</P>
<P>
Later, President and Mrs. Clinton were escorted by Governor
Cheng and Mayor Feng through the ancient gate into the city that
had been imperial capital with more than 1,000 years of history.
</P>
<P>
President and Mrs. Clinton mounted the wall gate tower, where
they looked around and waved to tens of thousands of local
well-wishers in acknowledgement. 
</P>
