<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference on Disarmament Ends 2nd Part of 1998 Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Conference on Disarmament (CD)
ended the second part of the 1998 session here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 61-member conference will resume on July 27 for the final
part of the 1998 session which will end on September 9.
</P>
<P>
During the second part of the session, 46 CD members and
observers signed a joint statement condemning nuclear testing in
May by India and then by Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The signatories "are alarmed and deeply concerned at nuclear
testing by India and Pakistan," said the statement drafted by
Australia and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
"They condemn all nuclear testing and consider such acts to be
contrary to the international consensus which bans the testing of
nuclear weapons and other explosive devices," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The tests undertaken by India and Pakistan's decision to
respond with its own tests blatantly undermine the international
regime of non-proliferation of nuclear weapons," it said. "The
actions of India and Pakistan threaten and undermine the process
of disarmament and the goal of eliminating nuclear weapons
altogether."
</P>
<P>
They called on India and Pakistan to resolve their tensions
"through constructive dialogue and negotiation."
</P>
<P>
Many members said that the nuclear tests last month in South
Asia should push the conference into action when it meets next
month.
</P>
<P>
"While we can honestly disagree about the scope of the work we
should undertake in the conference, we should at least be able to
agree on the facts regarding what has been achieved so far in
working toward nuclear disarmament," said U.S. Ambassador Robert
Grey Jr Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The issue of landmines could also be discussed next month at
the CD meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
