<HEADLINE> World Bank Opens Resident Mission Office in Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank officially
inaugurated its resident mission in Mongolia's capital,
Ulaanbaatar, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the establishment of the resident mission in
Ulaanbaatar, World Bank Country Director for Mongolia Ngozi
Okonjo-Iweala said, "We are pleased to be closer to our clients
and development partners and to be able to facilitate access to
the bank's global knowledge base."
</P>
<P>
Since Mongolia joined the World Bank Group in 1991, the country
has received the interest-free credits totaling 164 million U.S.
dollars for 10 projects from the International Development
Association, the bank's concessional lending arm for developing
countries. The annual lending program has averaged 25 to 30
million dollars equivalent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
