<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawi Involved in Machel's Death: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Graca Machel, the widow of
Mozambique's former president, has disclosed that Malawi agents
were among the conspirators who eliminated her husband in 1986.
</P>
<P>
Machel said this Tuesday at a hearing of the South Africa's
Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC), the Malawi News Agency
(MANA) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"I have no doubt that my husband died in a conspiracy
involving Mozambique, Malawi and South African agents," Machel
said in her four-hour testimony before the TRC.
</P>
<P>
During the hearing, the widow who is the companion of South
African President Nelson Mandela, cited names and people who
hatched the conspiracy and their dates of the meetings for the
planned assassination.
</P>
<P>
The apartheid South Africa then blamed bad weather and pilot
error for the plane crash which killed Samora Machel and 30
others inside South Africa over a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
But the Malawi Congress Party (MCP) in power during the crash,
has distanced itself and its government from the charge.
</P>
<P>
"The party and the government were not involved in other
countries' affairs or conflict," MANA quoted Hetherwick Ntaba,
the MCP treasurer general as saying Wendesday when it sought the
party's views on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Ntaba, however, said that Machel could be alluding to agents
who were not government or party officials but from other
countries and might have operated from Malawi, adding "Malawi had
a policy of peaceful co-existence then."
</P>
<P>
But Malawi's Defense Minister Joseph Kubwalo said the
allegations should not be dismissed because the MCP was involved
in a lot of sinister acts during its reign.
</P>
<P>
He regretted that the Machel saga was a very sad development
and the new Malawi which maintains very friendly relations with
Mozambique and South Africa "just fails short of apologizing for
what may have happened."
</P>
<P>
Kubwalo added that the Muluzi administration was willing to
assist the TRC or the Mozambican government in further inquiries
into the crash. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
