<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Still Exports Fish to EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Uganda is still exporting its
fish and fishery products to the European Union (EU) because it
has met a significant part of the standards of the 15-member
bloc, a press release has said.
</P>
<P>
The press release, issued Thursday by the Uganda National
Bureau of Standards (UNBS), stated that recent press reports are
not accurate when indicating that fish exports from east Africa,
including Uganda, to EU has been banned.
</P>
<P>
It said Uganda was placed on List 2 of countries allowed to
export fish and fishery products to Europe. The countries
grouped into this category are said to have satisfied most of the
EU requirements but are not fully harmonized because they need to
carry out more improvement.
</P>
<P>
Countries on this list are allowed to export fish to EU
through bilateral arrangements with EU member countries. In other
words, each EU member state can choose the establishments to deal
with.
</P>
<P>
Countries on List 1 are those which have been harmonized and
allowed to export fish products to the EU market without
particular limitations while countries on List 3 are those whose
evaluation is still pending or which have so far not achieved a
significant level of quality improvement.
</P>
<P>
An EU inspection team is to visit Uganda in September this
year to evaluate the fish processing industry with the view of
upgrading Uganda to List 1 if the EU requirements are met, the
press release added.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the temporary ban on export of chilled fish which
has been imposed by EU since December 1997 due to the outbreak of
cholera, the UNBS said the ban will be lifted from July 1, 1998.
The export of frozen fish products to EU, which has not been
affected by the above-mentioned temporary ban, continues.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's fish processing sector has expanded greatly in recent
years and current export earnings are in excess of 100 million
U.S. Dollars per year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
