<HEADLINE> Stakeholders, Donors Lose Confidence in Zambia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government
acknowledged Thursday that stakeholders and the donor community
have lost confidence in the agricultural sector investment
program (ASIP) because it has been poorly implemented.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a two-day meeting on the review of the program
held in Lusaka, Agricultural Minister Amusaa Mwanamwambwa said
the ASIP has not achieved the desired objectives to benefit the
country's small-scale farmers since it was implemented two and
half years ago, Zambia News Agency ZANA reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting attracted several high commissioners and
ambassadors accredited to Zambia as well as members of parliament
on the agricultural committee.
</P>
<P>
"There has been a serious erosion of stakeholders' confidence
in the ASIP program because it has not achieved the intended
objectives in the year under review," said the minister when
presenting a proposed action plan aimed at restructing the
program to make it more effective.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the program has been unable to attract donor
support because of its poor performance and stressed the need to
review it.
</P>
<P>
At the same meeting, George Mburathi, United Nations Food and
Agricultural Organization (FAO) representative in Zambia, also
stated that the ASIP has lost credibility in the eyes of the
donor community.
</P>
<P>
He called for the restructuring of the program if it has to
continue receiving donor support.
</P>
<P>
The FAO representative also called for renewed government
commitment toward the implementation of ASIP and the involvement
of the private sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
