<HEADLINE> Some Sidebars after Clinton's Arrival in Xi'an </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Following are some sidebars after
U.S. President Clinton's arrival in Xi'an City:
</P>
<P>
-- Twin Brother-Sister Presenting Flowers
</P>
<P>
As President Clinton alighted from Air Force One, a pair of
11-year-old twin brother-sister, who look very much alike,
stepped forward to present the president and the first lady with
fresh flowers and offered their regards in English.
</P>
<P>
Both are the fifth graders at the Kaitongxiang Primary School
in Xi'an. The elder brother is called Yu Zhengzhong and his
younger sister is Yu Zhengxin.
</P>
<P>
-- Clinton Awaiting Reporters in Limousine
</P>
<P>
After brief greetings with local officials at the airport, the
president stepped into his black Lincoln limousine which soon sped
to the ancient city of Xi'an behind police cars.
</P>
<P>
This worried scores of journalists who had the privileges to
cover the president within a short reach, because their bus was at
the back of a motorcade of 50 cars and arrived at the destination
five minutes later.
</P>
<P>
However, upon their arrival, the journalists were glad to see
that the president had just stepped out of his limousine and they
vied with eath other for vantage points at the south gate of the
City Wall.
</P>
<P>
-- Ancient Parade Ritual
</P>
<P>
The president was greeted at the south gate of Xi'an City Wall
with a ceremony that revived an ancient parade ritual in honor of
distinguished guests. The president and Mrs. Clinton walked along
an "imperial path" paved with red carpets, amid sounds of beating
60 huge drums, proceeded by 16 girls dressed in Tang Dynasty
costumes as maids of honor, and greeted by 300 teamed-up armored
warriors in the square.
</P>
<P>
-- Greetings by Xi'an Residents
</P>
<P>
In sharp contrast to the scorching heat in the past few days,
Xi'an residents enjoyed cooler weather and light cosy evening
breeze today as the motorcade of President Clinton passes along
the streets of Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
Over two hours ahead of Clinton's arrival, many people flocked
to the streets through which the president's motorcade might go.
As the vehicles with both Chinese and American flags went by,
people on both sides of the streets applauded enthusiastically.
</P>
</TEXT>
