<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Ancient Capital Opens Gate of Friendship for Clinton (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Accompanied by the Tang-style guest-greeting music, actors clad
in the formal attire of ancient Chinese officials and generals, in
armors of ancient warriors and actresses in Tang Dynasty costumes
filed out of the Gate to greet the U.S. president.
</P>
<P>
Clinton started his speech with the Chinese greeting words of
Nimen Hao, which won warm applause from his audience, and
expressed his respect for China's long civilization.
</P>
<P>
One of the four ancient capitals in the world, Xi'an has played
host to other distinguished guests including former U.S. President
Ronald Reagan, British Queen Elizabeth 2nd, and Japanese Emperor
Akihito.
</P>
<P>
The president and Mrs. Clinton then was led into the city gate
and mounted the gate tower for a night view of the city. The
president waved to local dwellers who thronged the ground beneath
the tower and was greeted by a splash of applauses and waving
hands from some nearby buildings.
</P>
<P>
"Xi'an was the starting point for the Silk Road that connected
the East with the West in ancient times." said Yue Yu, a professor
from Northwest University.
</P>
<P>
He added that President Jiang Zemin's successful visit to the
United States last fall strengthened the friendship between the
peoples of China and the U.S., and "we hope President Clinton's
visit will further the friendly ties between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
Clinton signed his name with a Chinese writing brush on the
visitors' book of the ancient city wall scenic zone after his
visit to the wall.  
</P>
</TEXT>
