<HEADLINE> Hamas Leader Reiterates Refusal to Join PNA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Hamas leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin
said Thursday he will not join the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) unless PNA President Yasser Arafat repudiates the Olso
Accords and take part in the struggle against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Yassin made the remarks at a news conference in Gaza, Israel
Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
PNA officials said that Arafat earlier asked Hamas to join his
cabinet as part of a reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
But Yassin, accusing the PNA of imprisoning Hamas members,
rejected the offer during his recent trip to Arab countries and
Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Hamas leader said that he would like to cease fire with
Israel if the Jewish state gives up all the Palestinian lands it
seized in the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
He has stressed on many occasions that Hamas would not stop its
"holy war" against Israel. He renewed his call for the destruction
of Israel during the news conference.
</P>
<P>
After wrapping up his four-month fundraising tour, Yassin
returned to Gaza late Wednesday night. He has reportedly raised 50
million U.S. dollars during his trip.
</P>
<P>
Israel fears that the funds will strengthen Hamas' military
factions. Yassin, however, has announced that the money will be
given to the poor, the families of prisoners and orphans.
</P>
<P>
PNA-controlled media did not report Yassin's return Wednesday
night. PNA sources said they do not expect Yassin to make any
immediate attempts to challenge the authority of Arafat, who is
working to form a new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
There was a lengthy debate in Israel over whether to let
Yassin back from his trip. After close-door discussions and
deliberations, security officials have recommended that Yassin be
allowed back, saying that he would cause less damage to Israel in
Gaza than he was abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
