<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Norway Provides $964,000 Aid for Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations humanitarian
aid agencies and the Norwegian government signed here Thursday an
agreement, under which Norway provides Angola with 964,000 U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian government made the grant in response to the
appeal by U.N. agencies to the international community to aid
Angola with a total of 91 million Dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Of the total 964,000 Dollars, 540,000 Dollars is for emergency
humanitarian aid, while the rest will be used for a rapid
response by the coordinative agency for humanitarian aid in times
of crisis in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Francesco Strippoli, representative of the coordinative agency
of humanitarian aid in Angola, signed the agreement with Bjorg
Leite, Norwegi Ambassador to Angola.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is very important. It indicates that the
international community will continue to assist Angola until its
wish of final peace is realized, said Strippoli.
</P>
<P>
According to the Norwegian ambassador, her government will
continue to provide aid to the poorest Angolans with an annual
aid total of 20 million to 25 million US Dollars until the
country passes the stage for emergency aid.
</P>
<P>
She also noted that the Norwegian government will also aid
Angola in its post-war rehabilitation and development.
</P>
<P>
Norway has been aiding Angola since 1980, mostly in the fields
of landmine-clearing, education, vocational education for the
demobilized as well as the repairs on infrastructure destroyed
during the two-decade long war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
