<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV Carriers to Climb Kilimanjaro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Eight HIV carriers, including
five Africans and three Europeans, will set out from the Kenyan
capital to climb Africa's highest mountain Kilimanjaro, a report
reaching here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The team, three of them women, planned to officially start the
four-day climbing on June 29 and to reach the 5,895-meter peak on
July 1 so as to coincide the 12th World AIDS Conference in
Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The African climbers are from Kenya, Ivory Coast, Burkina Faso
and South Africa. Two of their European teammates are French,
the other one is a Swiss.
</P>
<P>
Etienne Tape Be, a 26-year-old climber from Ivory Coast, works
with the Abidjan-based Action Lumiere -- one of many support
groups springing up in Africa as the epidemic rages on.
</P>
<P>
"When I found out I was HIV positive in 1994 I was absolutely
crushed for two days. Then I said to myself that I would show I
could deal with it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Joyce Malope, a 24-year-old South African, was infected during
a rape. Kenyan Ruth Wambui is a 37-year-old mother with six
children.
</P>
<P>
About 21 million of the world's estimated 31 million people
infected with HIV, the virus that causes the lethal AIDS, live in
sub-Saharan Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
