<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Nears Self-sufficiency in Wood, Wood Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The addition of Austria, Finland
and Sweden has given a dramatic boost to European Union (EU)
forestry self-sufficiency, Eurostat reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
After the EU enlargement to include the three countries, said
the Luxembourg-based EU statistical office, per capita forest land
area in the union rose from 0.15 hectares to 0.27 hectares.
</P>
<P>
By almost doubling the forest land to 102,325,000 hectares and
adding the forestry industry in Finland and Sweden, it said, the
15-nation union is now 91 percent self-sufficient in sawnwood.
</P>
<P>
The sawnwood self-sufficiency rate before the inclusion of the
three countries into the regional alliance was 55 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
In printing and writing paper, the EU was 118 percent
self-sufficient in 1996 compared with 78 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Finland and Sweden, three other EU member states of
France, Germany and Spain also boast forest land area of more than
10 million hectares, said the EU statistics clearing house.
</P>
<P>
Finland and Sweden are described by Eurostat as key market
players in coniferous sawnwood, woodpulp, paper and paperboard
products as well, with their exports mainly within the union.
</P>
<P>
In roundwood, however, EU self-sufficiency has slightly
diminished as Finland and Sweden import significant amounts of
roundwood from outside the union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
