<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Jute Organization Seeks to Renew Jute Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The International Jute Organization
(IJO) will make efforts to get renewed a U.N. agreement which gave
birth to the Dhaka-based organization, the national news agency
BSS reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The existence of the IJO would be at stake if the International
Agreement on Jute and Jute Products signed in 1982 could not be
renewed before it expires in April 2000, IJO Executive Director
Henri L Jason was quoted by the BSS as saying here Friday.
</P>
<P>
A preparatory committee, comprising all the IJO members, has
decided recently to strongly pursue the extension of the U.N.
agreement for the continuity of the IJO, he said.
</P>
<P>
The extension of the agreement and the participation of India,
which expressed its intention to withdraw from the organization in
May, are necessary to continue the role the IJO has been playing
between jute exporters and importers for the past decade,
according to Jason.
</P>
<P>
And this is essential to consolidate the successes the IJO has
made in research for high-yielding varieties, market promotion,
and diversification of jute and jute goods, he added.
</P>
<P>
Iran and a Brazilian state have expressed the desire to join
the IJO, and efforts are being made to get Cote d'Lvoire,
Cameroon, Ghana and Nigeria as new members of the IJO, the IJO
executive director said.
</P>
<P>
The IJO, which is carrying out activities under three sections
- the agriculture, industry, and market promotion, was established
in 1984 to implement the provisions of the international
agreement, which was replaced by a similar agreement in 1989.
</P>
<P>
The IJO now groups 27 members, including five exporting
countries - Bangladesh, China, India, Nepal and Thailand, and 21
importing members including Britain, France, Germany, Indonesia,
Pakistan and Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
