<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Water Level Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The water level of the Yangtze
River continues to rise and the banks along the 195-km section
in Jiujiang City in East China's Jiangxi Province faces the danger
of being breached.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rain today pushed up the water level at the Jiujiang
section to 20.37 meters, 0.87 meters above the danger
level. Boyang Lake, one of the few major lakes along the Yangtze,
also saw its water level standing at dangerous levels.
</P>
<P>
Inside Jiujiang City, nearly 4,000 houses were damaged and over
33,333 ha of crops were affected. Some sections of the highways
were also disrupted.
</P>
<P>
Meteorological departments predicted that the water level in
Yangtze and the lake will further rise to 22 meters and 21.9
meters respectively in the coming four days.
</P>
<P>
Acting mayor Liu Jifu said that the city has mobilized a rescue
force of over 100,000 people, armed with bags of grass, cobble
stones and wooden sticks.
</P>
<P>
The Jiujiang section of river banks have not been built to the
standard in terms of height and solidarity. From last December to
March this year, 16 sections of the banks collapsed  
</P>
</TEXT>
