<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Slightly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar spent the
day struggling to break free from its ties with the besieged
Japanese yen and at the same time managed to gain ground against
the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The volatile local currency stayed above the key psychological
level of 60 U.S. cents despite weakness in regional partners, the
yen and the New Zealand dollar.
</P>
<P>
"There are already signs that the Australian currency is
decoupling from yen," HSBC Markets chief economist John Edwards
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Citibank chief economist Stephen Koukoulas noted the
Australian dollar had edged higher against the yen.
</P>
<P>
At the close in Sydney, the Australian currency was at 60.68
U.S. cents Friday from 60.45 U.S. cents previously.
</P>
<P>
Treasury Secretary Ted Evans said Australia's currency had been
hurt because dealers wrongly linked Australia to the Asian
economic crisis, but they now appeared to be separating Australia
from the rest of the region.
</P>
<P>
"To align those two currencies makes very little sense at all,
but markets, as I say, look at Asia in total," Evans said.
</P>
<P>
"Interestingly, since the yen began to weaken again in recent
days, that has not been the case, and we've actually strengthened
against the yen."
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar also closed the week at 86.12 yen from
85.11 yen and 1.0906 German marks from 1.0852 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
