<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Calls for Economic Coop With S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques
Chirac Friday called for more economic cooperation between France
and South Africa, saying French business was ready to play a
bigger role in the local economy.
</P>
<P>
Chirac arrived in South Africa Friday for a three-day state
visit.
</P>
<P>
In a speech prepared for delivery at the French-South African
Economic Forum in Midrand near here, Chirac lamented France's
weak image in the region and called for increased efforts to
highlight the two countries' strengths to promote more economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said France was Africa's leading supplier and accounted for
about 16 percent of African imports in the last five years --
twice more than Germany and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Africa was also France's second largest market outside the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, accounting
for almost five percent of its total export sales.
</P>
<P>
Noting that trade between South Africa and the rest of the
continent had doubled since 1994, Chirac said fears that France
and South Africa would become rivals on the continent were
unfounded.
</P>
<P>
"Our two countries do not compete but complement each other in
Africa. Fir, because South Africa's areas of excellence in
Africa differ significantly from ours.
</P>
<P>
"Secondly, because our geographical focus differs, France's
position is especially strong in north and west Africa. South
Africa continues to focus primarily on southern Africa, which
accounts for two-thirds of its African exports, and to a lesser
extent, on east Africa," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said bilateral assistance to South Africa, independent
of the aid channelled through the European Union, amounted to
half a billion Rand (90.1 million U.S. Dollars). This was more
than most other assistance from the international community.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the volume of French export sales to South Africa
rose by 27 percent compared to the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, French investments in South Africa came to more
than three billion Rand (545 million Dollars), reflecting the
interest of French companies in the country and their confidence
in its future, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
