<HEADLINE> Stocks Close Firmer on Strong Australian Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket Friday
closed higher on the back of a stronger Australian dollar,
positive leads from northern hemisphere markets and resources
giant BHP finally putting its house in order.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index closed up 17.9 points, or
0.69 percent, at 2,609.9, but off a high of 2,614.3. It reached a
low of 2,590.1.
</P>
<P>
"I guess the reasons were a bit of delayed reaction from the
gains on overseas markets over the past few days and the fact that
the Australian dollar held up reasonably well despite the Japanese
yen weakness," a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Shares in resources giant BHP gained 19 cents, or 1.41 percent,
to 13.70 Australian dollars on a turnover of 15.13 million shares
after the company posted its second ever loss in its 113-year
history.
</P>
<P>
BHP announced a massive 3.049 billion Australian dollars (1.829
billion U.S. dollars) in asset writedowns, and reported an annual
loss of 1.47 billion Australian dollars (882 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index closed up 34.4 points at 4,563.7 and
the all resources index closed up 4.1 points at 1,036.2.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 386.2 million valued at 1.56 billion
Australian dollars (936 million U.S. dollars), with falls
outnumbering rises by 552 to 536, and 484 stocks remaining steady.
</P>
<P>
In the bank sector, National Australia Bank dipped 9.9 cents to
21.051 Australian dollars, ANZ Banking Group rose 21 cents to
11.13 Australian dollars, Commonwealth Bank of Australia gained 32
cents to 18.35 Australian dollars and Westpac Banking Corp climbed
eight cents to 9.82 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
St George Bank, the fifth largest retail bank in Australia,
gained 31 cents, or 3.16 percent, to 10.11 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere, global miner Rio Tinto gained eight to 19.10
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed up 2.7 points, or 0.26 percent, at
1,046.2.
</P>
<P>
Sydney trade in gold bullion closed 1.10 U.S. dollars higher at
293.94 U.S. dollars an ounce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
