<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Accord on Banana Import Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) agriculture
ministers agreed Friday on the tariff rate for both tariff quota
and autonomous quota of banana imports.
</P>
<P>
Containing changes proposed by the European Commission (EC),
the executive body of the 15-nation union, the accord was
finalized after four days of intensive debate.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler described the accord as
both fully respecting EU's World Trade Organization obligations
and ensuring EU consumer and producer interests.
</P>
<P>
Under the new document, the EU's tariff quota of 2.2 million
metric tons of banana import would remain unchanged at a tariff
rate of 75 European currency unit (ECU) per ton.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, said an EU spokesman, the tariff rate for the
autonomous quota of 353,000 tons of banana imports would also be
fixed at 75 ECU per ton.
</P>
<P>
It is now up to the EU council of ministers' decision about the
tariff rate for the autonomous quota, otherwise the rate could
vary a great deal, said the official spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The EC proposed a cut of tariff rate for the autonomous quota
from 300 ECU per ton to 75 ECU per ton as a support for the banana
producers in the Africa, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) region.
</P>
<P>
Banana-producing countries in the EU like France and Spain,
however, were promised an increase in aid for their growers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
