<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Calls on Eritrea to Respect Rights of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia Friday asks the
international community to put pressure on the Eritrean
authorities to respect the rights of Ethiopian citizens who are
living presently in Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The office of the Ethiopian government spokesperson says in a
news release issued here that more than six hundred Ethiopians
have been detained in Eritrea since the border conflict began in
early May.
</P>
<P>
"Though they have committed no offense they continue to be
exposed to the worst form of torture, atrocities and inhumane
treatment and are denied the freedom to leave Eritrea," the
office states, adding that "the Red Cross and journalists have
been denied access to them and their families have had no news of
them since they were rounded up and imprisoned in the early
stages of the conflict."
</P>
<P>
The office calls on the international community to put
pressure on the Eritrean side to allow access to these detainees
and to push for their release and safe conduct to Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The office continues to say that well over 4,000 Ethiopians
were arrested, some were beaten and tortured, their property was
confiscated and they were driven to the border with Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
"Some were deprived of their medical treatment in the
process," said the release.
</P>
<P>
According to an announcement made by the office last week, the
Ethiopian government had held 140 Eritrean national conscripts at
a center in the town of of Fiche, about 100 km north of Addis
Ababa for reasons of national security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
