<HEADLINE> Mugabe Calls for Constitutional Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
said Friday debate on the need to revamp Zimbabwe's constitution
should be done within and outside the ruling party to come up
with a draft document to be put to the people in a referendum.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe told the 34th ordinary session of ruling Zimbabwe
African National Union Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF) central
committee that the aim of the government was to get view points
from the party as well as those of others to ensure the new
constitution would be coming from the people, the Zimbabwe News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"I hope and trust that our legal and constitutional committee
has now done enough preparatory work on the subject of amending
the present constitution so discussion can start soon," said
Mugabe, who is ZANU-PF's first secretary.
</P>
<P>
The president urged other political parties and interested
organizations to "have the freedom" of enunciating their own
beliefs and view points.
</P>
<P>
"This is so that whatever definite and positive issues emerge
are included in a proposed constitutional document to be put to
the people at a referendum, since it is now agreed among us that
this be the mode of securing national acceptance or rejection of
such a document," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Civic organization, under the National Constitutional
Assembly, have since last year started consulting people on the
need for total reform.
</P>
<P>
Several legislators have also openly spoken on the need to
revamp the constitution.
</P>
<P>
"If democracy is to thrive and become a national heritage,
then the nation's political course to change government or its
leadership can only be that of an orderly democratic process as
prescribed by our constitution," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
He again blamed social disturbances in the country over price
increases on the Zimbabwe Congress of Trade Unions, the workers
and tertiary and university students.
</P>
<P>
The president also castigated some leaders within the party
"who, for their own ambitious reasons, have wished for, and
indeed have clandestinely given support to anti-government
activities that have the makings of instigating mass uprisings."
</P>
</TEXT>
