<HEADLINE> China Cracks Down on Illegal Publications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- China is waging a nationwide
campaign to crack down on illegal publications, with the effort
including the destruction of millions of pirated VCDs, tapes and
illegal publications over the past few days alone.
</P>
<P>
For example, south China's Guangdong Province destroyed some
2.8 million pirated VCDs on June 15 as part of what was reportedly
the country's most extensive effort to eliminate pirated VCDs.
</P>
<P>
Beijing, the Chinese capital, has also maintained tight
controls on illegal publications, with over 150,000 pirated VCDs
and 100,000 illegal books and periodicals destroyed on June 16 and
17.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin has destroyed more than 60,000 pirated VCDs and
numerous illegal publications, while Chongqing has destroyed
150,000 pirated VCDs and 200,000 illegal books and periodicals.
</P>
<P>
Shangdong Province has joined in the effort by destroying some
350,000 pirated VCDs and illegal audiovisual products and
publications.
</P>
<P>
Provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities nationwide are
joining in the extensive effort.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
