<HEADLINE> Feature: Early Birds Visit Drug Exhibition (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of people queued in front
of Beijing's Military Museum of the Chinese People's Revolution at
06:00 this morning to await the opening of National Anti-Drug
Exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Cui Guangwei, an official with the China National Petroleum
Corporation, stood in the queue with his family. "Many of my
colleagues have visited the exhibition and agree to the
instructional benefits of the event. My entire family came early
to see for ourselves." said Cui.
</P>
<P>
Deng Ming, a member of the organizing committee, said the
exhibition, the largest of its kind since the founding of the
People's Republic of China in 1949, has attracted more than half a
million visitors since opening on May 29. He noted that the event
was extended for an extra month in answer to the strong demand.
</P>
<P>
"Over 250,000 people reserved tickets on the day following the
announcement of the extension," said Deng.
</P>
<P>
The fact that Chinese news media exhibited unprecedented
enthusiasm for publicizing of the exhibition has made the
event a hot topic of discussion amongst the general public.
</P>
<P>
Deng stressed that the anti-drug effort requires the support
and understanding of people from all walks of life. He noted that
people from all circles have expressed concern over the issue and
praised the tremendous success of the exhibition.
</P>
</TEXT>
