<HEADLINE> Japan: Clinton's China Visit of Global Significance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Japan on Friday welcomed
U.S. President Bill Clinton's historical visit to China, saying
the tour was "important" to the whole world.
</P>
<P>
"Good and stable relations which would be built through
President Clinton's visit to China this time are important" not
only for the Asia-Pacific region but the world at large, Japanese
Foreign Ministry spokesman Sadaaki Numata said.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton on Thursday kicked off his landmark nine-day
China trip from June 25 through July 3, the first by an American
president since George Bush's trip in February 1989.
</P>
<P>
On Clinton's Saturday summit meeting with Chinese President
Jiang Zemin in Beijing, Numata said, "Japan should welcome it
because it would give new momentum to Sino-U.S. relations."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also called for reinforcement of the tripartite
links among Japan, China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Japan expects to hear the results of Clinton's tour of China
when U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright pays her scheduled
visit to Japan on July 3. 
</P>
