<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Raises Water Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Singaporeans will pay more money
for domestic water consumption from next month as the government
is mounting on more efforts to slow down the growth of water
consumption.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Trade and Industry Lee Yock Suan announced Friday
that the water tariff, including the water conservation tax, will
be increased by up to 24 Singapore cents per cubic meters for home
users with effect from 1 July.
</P>
<P>
He made the announcement when he launched the "Save Water
Campaign" this year.
</P>
<P>
This is the second rise since last year in what will be a
series of four annual increments on 1 July 1997, 1998, 1999 and
2000, which target water tariff at 1.52 Singapore dollars (about
0.92 U.S. dollars) per cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
The present water tariff rate is 73 cents per cubic meters and
the water conservation tax rate stands 10 per cent.
</P>
<P>
The minister said there will be no increase for non-domestic
consumers as they are already paying close to the target rate of
1.52 Singapore dollars per cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that the waterborne fee, which goes towards
treating waters and sewerage facilities, will also be raised by 5
cents per cubic meters for domestic consumers and 10 cents per
cubic meters for non-domestic users starting on the same day.
</P>
<P>
The minister said water consumption has been rising fast with
the annual growth rate increasing from 4.2 percent in 1996 to 5
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
The domestic sector, which accounts for about half of the water
consumption, registered a 3.3 percent increase in 1997 compared
with a 0.9 percent rise in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Noting Singapore is an island country with scarce water
resources, the minister said the government has adopted a
two-pronged approach: first by pricing water correctly; and
secondly by getting the public to make it a habit to conserve
water.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the economic downturn, we must press on with our water
conservation efforts and raise water tariffs and conservation tax
as planned," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Drug Education Proposed in Pre-Marriage Courses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's National Anti-Drug
Council is proposing that anti-drug curriculum be incorporated in
pre-marriage courses in the country, Deputy Home Minister Ong Ka
Ting said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The council proposed that Muslim and non-Muslim couples be also
taught about measures against having drug-dependent children in
the family later, he said.
</P>
<P>
Because parenting skills have long been ignored, the council
proposed that state Islamic affairs departments incorporate
anti-drug curriculum in pre-marriage courses for Muslim couples,
he said.
</P>
<P>
As for non-Muslim couples, the deputy minister said the
National Registration Department, which also registers marriages,
should conduct such courses.
</P>
<P>
"Being parents is not an easy task in this modern era. We tend
to totally let the school take care of our children while we are
so preoccupied with eking out a livelihood. I think this is no
longer suitable with the present challenges," he was quoted by
Malaysia's national news agency Bernama as telling reporters after
a function in Kuala Kerai in the northern state of Kelantan.
</P>
<P>
Ong also urged the Civil Defense Department to adopt a
front-line role in the fight against the drug menace, especially
in educating the people on the perils of drug-abuse as well as the
preventive measures.
</P>
<P>
Today is the International Day Against Drug Abuse and Illicit
trafficking, with the theme "Youth Uniting to Prevent Drug Abuse"
for this year.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, Malaysia's National Association for the
Prevention of Drug Abuse meanwhile urged all Malaysian youths to
unite and reject drugs to achieve the government target of a
drug-free Malaysia within 25 years.
</P>
<P>
The association's Vice President Lee Lam Thye said in a
statement issued Friday that as the future leaders of the nation,
Malaysian youths must be fully equipped to face multiple
challenges and be free from drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
Lee suggested that all schools intensify drug prevention
educational campaigns and include more anti-drug programs in their
extra curricular activities.
</P>
<P>
He said all youth organizations in Malaysia should give
priority to drug abuse prevention programs by setting up anti-drug
units and organizing more awareness campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Lee also suggested that non-governmental voluntary
organizations work together with government agencies to organize
and implement anti-drug abuse programs involving youth and youth
organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
