<HEADLINE> Employees of Nepal Airlines on Hunger Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Employees of the Royal Nepal
Airlines Corporation (RNAC) including pilots resumed their
domestic flights Friday after a one-day strike Thursday, but they
started a relay hunger strike instead to pressure the management
to meet their demands.
</P>
<P>
The relay hunger strike took place on the RNAC premises and
will last three days after talks between the Employees
Coordination Committee and the management failed.
</P>
<P>
The committee threatened to launch stronger protest programs if
its demands are not met by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Employees Coordination Committee presented an ultimatum to
the chairman of RNAC on June 11, demanding hiring of planes on
lease-purchase basis instead of short-term leasing of aircraft
from foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
The committee also demands the immediate formulation and
implementation of new regulations and ending of financial
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
The national flag carrier of Nepal has only two Boeing 757 jets
and has a Boeing 737 on a short-term lease.
</P>
<P>
For years, the airlines officials have been alleged with
pocketing huge commissions on the leases while the airlines runs
with a loss of 180 million rupees (2.7 million U.S. dollars) on
the domestic route alone.
</P>
<P>
"The management is ready to solve the problem through talks,
but they should resume work," said K.B. Poudel, spokesman of RNAC.
</P>
<P>
The strike has not affected the airlines' international
flights.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
