<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Manufacturing Output Drops In May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's manufacturing output
declined by 4.5 percent in May this year compared to the same
month of last year, the Economic Development Board said in a press
release Friday.
</P>
<P>
The EDB said the fall was caused by lower output from the
electronics cluster despite increases in both chemicals and
engineering clusters.
</P>
<P>
Output from the electronics cluster was down by 9.6 percent
from May 1997 with all its major segments, except computer
peripherals and PCBAs, dipping below levels of a year ago, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Weak demand lowered the output levels of personal computers and
telecommunication equipment while the persistent market oversupply
continued to depress the output of disk drives and affect the
semiconductors segment, it added.
</P>
<P>
According to EDB, output of petrochemicals, the top riser among
all segments, grew by 15.7 percent in May thanks to the new and
higher capacities in the industry despite some maintenance
shutdowns. The chemicals clusters registered a 4.9 percent growth,
the pharmaceuticals segment increased by 6.3 percent, and the
petroleum industry grew by 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the engineering sector which only grew 0.6 percent, the
decline in the precision engineering segment was almost nullified
by increases in the transport and processing engineering segment.
</P>
</TEXT>
