<HEADLINE> UN Envoy Visits Dhaka on South Asian Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A special envoy of United Nations
Secretary General Kofi Annan arrived here Friday for consultations
with Bangladesh leaders on the U.N.'s possible role in reducing
tension in South Asia in the aftermath of nuclear blasts by India
and Pakistan last month.
</P>
<P>
Alvaro De Soto, U.N. assistant secretary general for political
affairs, is expected to meet Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Part of his mission was to prepare ground for a possible visit
by Annan himself to the region, a press report said.
</P>
<P>
The envoy, who is carrying a letter from Annan for Hasina, is
scheduled to fly to Karachi, Pakistan, Saturday after his one-day
Bangladesh visit.
</P>
<P>
India is against outside involvement in resolving its disputes
with Pakistan, while the latter favors the U.N. or any third party
helping in this regard.
</P>
<P>
India would refuse to receive the U.N. envoy, Indian Foreign
Ministry spokesman Sunil Lal said Thursday, according to reports
reaching here. "They are talking about Indo-Pakistan matters and
Kashmir. You know our stand," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hasina visited India and Pakistan on June 16 and 24
respectively, in an effort to mediate between her country's two
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
As the first foreign head of government to visit the two
countries after their nuclear explosions, Hasina was given a warm
welcome at the airport by Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif,
and in New Delhi, she had to confine her talks with her Indian
counterpart, Atal Bihari Vajpayee, on bilateral relations, reports
said. 
</P>
