<HEADLINE> Nepali Govt, Donors Meet on Water Supply Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government on Friday
held a meeting with donors interested in the Melamchi Water Supply
Project which aims to alleviate the chronic water shortage in the
Kathmandu Valley, the Asian Development Bank (ADB) said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting focused on the details of a private sector
management contract and the establishment of a regulatory
authority for urban water supply in the Kathmandu Valley, and
discussed who will own, fund, design, construct and manage the
various components of the project.
</P>
<P>
It also discussed the composition and functions of the Melamchi
Water Supply Board which will oversee the project and make all
major decisions, the ADB said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The Melamchi Water Supply Project has been conceived by the
Nepali government as a means to alleviate the chronic water
shortage in the Kathmandu Valley. The Melamchi river lies about 40
kilometers northeast of Kathmandu.
</P>
<P>
Donors have shown considerable interest in funding various
components of the project, which include headworks, tunnel,
hydropower plant, water treatment plant, bulk distribution and
distribution rehabilitation, the ADB said.
</P>
<P>
They have been discussing with the Nepali government the
conditions under which they will contribute to the project, the
bank said, adding that most conditions relate to commitment that
the project will be well-managed and sustainable.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the World Bank, the ADB, the United
Nations Development Program, Norway, Japan, Sweden and Denmark
attended the meeting, the ADB said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
