<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Cites Policies Protecting Tibetan Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Ye Xiaowen, director of the State
Bureau of Religious Affairs, today described claims that the
traditional culture in Tibet is dying as nothing more than "pure
lies".
</P>
<P>
Speaking at today's press conference, Ye said the Chinese
government has adopted a series of policies to promote the
development of ethnic cultures and ensure they receive proper
respect.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Constitution and the law governing the regional
autonomy of ethnic minorities contain special articles stressing
the protection and development of ethnic cultures, said Ye.
</P>
<P>
The central government has extended great effort to protect,
restore or preserve precious cultural relics and restore buildings
in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The central treasury has allocated a total of 300 million yuan
(37.5 million US dollars) since 1980 to repair and restore
cultural relics, including the world-famous Potala Palace, and the
Johkang, Baiqoi and Samyai monasteries. The government has also
funded the construction of a temple to commemorate the 10th
Panchen Lama.
</P>
<P>
The well-known 62-part Tibetan folk epic "King Gesser" has been
compiled and published in the Tibetan language. The Chinese
Tripitaka in both the Chinese and Tibetan languages and various
other Tibetan religious classics have also been released,
according to Ye.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 institutes for Tibetan studies are distributed
throughout the nation and the Tibetan language is taught and
widely used in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Certain people seem to derive pleasure out of creating lies
and spreading rumors," said Ye. adding that "rumors and lies never
succeed in distorting reality."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
