<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 200 AIDS Babies Born Each Day in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- At least 200 HIV-positive
babies are born in South Africa each day and it is estimated
that, within the next 10 years, up to three million children
could be infected or orphaned by the epidemic, The Star daily
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
AIDS specialists agree that about six percent of all babies in
South Africa are born with HIV.
</P>
<P>
The Health Department confirmed that 1.3 million babies were
born last year, which means that 78,000 babies were born
HIV-positive, or 214 a day.
</P>
<P>
Most babies contract the AIDS virus from mothers who are
HIV-positive, during birth or through breastfeeding, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
AIDS consultant Clive Evian said: "About 20 percent of women
who give birth in public health hospitals are HIV infected. One
out of four women then pass it on."
</P>
<P>
He said 30 to 40 percent of the babies died within the first
year.
</P>
<P>
Daya Moodley, senior research scientist at King Edward
Hospital in Durban, said the hospital recorded about 12,000
births a year, and 28 percent of the mothers were HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
Glenda Gray, director of Chris Hani Baragwanath's perinatal
HIV research unit, confirmed that, of the 20,000 women giving
birth at the hospital in a year, 4,000 were HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
Last year the Health Department undertook the eighth in a
series of unlinked, anonymous surveys of women attending
antenatal clinics of the public health service. Of 12,343
specimens screened, 1,976 (16,01 percent) were infected with HIV.
</P>
<P>
HIV (human immuno-deficiency virus) leads to full blown AIDS
(acquired immuno-deficiency syndrome).
</P>
<P>
Every day, about 1,200 new HIV infections are recorded among
adults, mostly in the 15- to 49-year age group.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic places a strain not only on the health system but
also on the welfare system as hundreds of thousands of children
are orphaned by the disease.
</P>
<P>
Gray said the country would need thousands of hospices to
treat AIDS children. "We need clear guidelines on how to take
care of them. A model for some form of home-based care is going
to be essential," she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Weed in Lake Victoria Reaches Crisis Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The water hyacinth, which is
currently covering 4,000 hectares on Lake Victoria, have reached
the crisis level, Uganda's National Environment Management
Authority (NEMA) said.
</P>
<P>
Aryamanya Mugisha, the NEMA deputy director, issued the
warning Thursday at a one-day sensitization seminar on
environmental management here.
</P>
<P>
"The water hyacinth problem has reached an environmental
crisis level now covering over 4,000 hectares of Lake Victoria
with 70 percent of the lake shoreline in Uganda covered," he was
quoted by Friday's Monitor paper as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the lake is estimated to contain over 1.25 million
metric tonnes of the weed and the situation is worsening because
another 3.5 million tonnes of the weed are currently flowing from
River Kagera in western Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The floating of the weed has hampered the country's power
generation and fishing activities.
</P>
<P>
The Owen Falls Dam in Jinja, which is located some 80 kms east
of Kampala and is generating 70 percent of the 230 megawatts of
electricty the country needs, has to take immediate measures to
clear the large stretches of water hyacinth hampering the
operation of the machines.
</P>
<P>
Fishermen's boats are sometimes barred from going out to the
lake or returning to the landing sites because of the weed,
dramatically reducing the their daily fish catches.
</P>
<P>
On the same seminar, Minister of Water, Lands and Environment
Henry Muganwa Kajura told the army officers to become the pillars
of "green peace" in the country.
</P>
<P>
He urged soldiers to put up coordination units in each
division to coordinate environmental protection activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
