<HEADLINE> UNITA Leader Savimbi to Reside in Luanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Jonas Savimbi, Chairman of the
opposition National Union for Total Independence of Angola, will
come to live in the capital city of Luanda.
</P>
<P>
General Secretary of UNITA Lukamba Gato made it public in the
central city of Andulo where UNITA's headquarters is located,
the Angolan News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Gato said that as the leader of the biggest opposition party,
Savimbi will reside in the political center of the country
so as to better lead the activities of UNITA.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the UNITA cadres holding positions in the
newly-established local governments at various levels to go to
their posts as soon as possible to carry out their
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
Cease-fire does not mean peace for all, Gato said, adding that
the true realization of peace needs such criteria as national
reconciliation, mutual acceptance between the two warring sides,
mutual accommodation, justice and democracy.
</P>
<P>
He said that UNITA has made great efforts for the achievement
of peace, including demobilizing 70,000 fighters, incorporating
nine generals into the national army and putting 273 areas
formerly controlled by it under the governance of the Angolan
government.
</P>
<P>
UNITA will continue its efforts to help resolve the pending
issues in the peace process in line with the 1994 Lusaka Peace
Protocol.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council adopted a resolution on June 12,
saying that U.N. will impose sanctions upon
UNITA on June 25 if the opposition group refused to surrender the
four "sensitive areas", Andulo, Bailundo, Nharea and Mungo to the
government by June 23. The sanctions include freezing savings
abroad of UNITA and its leaders and banning its export of diamonds.
</P>
<P>
At a peace process joint committee meeting later, UNITA expressed
its willingness to hand over the four areas, but a few days later
than the U.N.-set date.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, the U.N. Security Council held
meeting Wednesday, postponing until July 1 the date of imposing
the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council said that the sanctions would be in force
from four a.m. (gmt) on July 1 if UNITA refuses to surrender the
four areas unconditionally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
