<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Foreign Reserves Hit 7.58 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's foreign reserves
increased to 7.58 billion U.S. Dollars last year from 4.07
billion U.S. Dollars in 1996, the Central Bank of Nigeria has
announced.
</P>
<P>
In its latest issue of annual report available here Friday,
the bank said, "The restrained monetary stance pursued during
the year and appropriately supported by sustained fiscal prudence
contributed to the deliberation of the inflation rate from 29.3
percent in 1996 to single digit level of 8.5 percent in 1997."
</P>
<P>
Aggregate production, measured by gross domestic product at
constant prices, rose by 3.8 percent in 1997, compared with 3.4
percent in the previous year. But it fell below the 5.5-percent
target, the bank said in the report and its statement of
account for the year ended in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
The bank attributed the slow economic growth mainly to
low-level of investment, deteriorating infrastructural
facilities, persistent fuel scarcity, incessant power cuts and
inefficiency of other public utilities.
</P>
<P>
As for the performance of the bank itself, a surplus of 2.31
billion Naira (some 269 million U.S. Dollars) was attained in the
bank's financial operations last year, compared with 275.3
million Naira (about 3.21 million U.S. Dollars) in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
