<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Releases 17 More Political Detainees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has ordered
the release of 17 more political prisoners and detainees 11 days
after the release of nine detainees.
</P>
<P>
David Attach, the Chief Press Secretary to Head of State
General Abdulsalam Abubakakr, announced this in a statement in
Abuja Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the release of the detainees was
carried out in "furtherance of the new administration's
determination to strengthen the process of national
reconciliation."
</P>
<P>
Among the released detainees are Chief Lou Falae, former
Secretary to the Government of the Federation; Alhaji Abubakar
Rime, former Kano State Governor; Olisa Agbakoba and Segun
Maiyegun, human rights activists.
</P>
<P>
Others are Frederick Fasheun, former presidential aspirant in
the Social Democratic Party (SDP); Alhaji Sule Lamido, former SDP
chieftain; Ayo Opadokun, chieftain of the opposition group the
National Democratic Coalition.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, General Abubakar also appealed to the
released to reciprocate this gesture on keeping the peace and
contributing positively to the national reconciliation process.
</P>
<P>
On June 15, the Nigerian government announced the release of
nine political detainees, including former head of state General
Olusegun Obasanjo. Others are labor union and opposition
leaders, human rights activists and journalists.
</P>
<P>
The goodwill gesture has been welcomed both in and outside
Nigeria, and led to the thawing of the diplomatic ice between
Nigeria and the West.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony
Blair have both called Abubakar on the phone, expressing their
appreciation of the new leader's reconciliation efforts and urged
him to carry on the transition to democracy process.
</P>
<P>
A European Union delegation headed by British Foreign Minister
Tony Lloyd arrived in Nigeria Thursday afternoon and is expected
to meet General Abubakar Friday.
</P>
<P>
Upon arriving at the Lagos airport, Lloyd said that he will
discuss with Abubakar about EU sanctions, the democratization
process and air ban, among other issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
