<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Adopts Plan to Tackle Millennium Bug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has approved an
action plan to ensure the country's readiness for the year 2000
millennium bug, Y2K.
</P>
<P>
The plan, approved by the cabinet Wednesday, also paves the
way for introducing anti-dumping legislation for non-compliant
equipment and software, the report said, Business Day paper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Posts, Telecommunications and Broadcasting Minister Jay Naidoo
said Thursday that the government will urgently examine
regulations to ensure dumping in this area does not happen.
</P>
<P>
If necessary, new legislation against dumping of non-compliant
equipment and software will be introduced, he said.
</P>
<P>
The action plan, drawn up by the National Year 2000 Decision
Support Center (National Y2K Center), would ensure that 68
"mission-critical" systems within government are totally ready by
2000, Naidoo said.
</P>
<P>
The government could not afford to have these systems fail,
which includes those for pensions, examinations, housing
subsidies and transport, he said.
</P>
<P>
Assessment and analysis, planning, integration, testing and
implementation of the plan designed to save these systems will be
carried out under the guidance of the National Y2K Center.
</P>
<P>
Announcing that August 19, the 500th day before January 1,
2000, had been declared a national Y2K awareness day, Naidoo said
a meeting of all national and provincial directors-general would
be convened by the deputy president's office to ensure
implementation of the plan.
</P>
<P>
A nationwide survey showed that 70 percent of government
departments and 90 percent of large organizations anticipated
completing their conversions on time, Naidoo said.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of local authorities would also be ready,
although the figure excluded "embedded" systems within local
authorities, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Naidoo said the "low-level of readiness" among
government departments are of concern. A much bigger proportion
of government departments and local authorities lack adequately
skilled projects teams and adequate action plans compared with
that of large organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
