<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Urges New Tests on Warheads Unearthed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 26 (Xinhua)-- Iraq has urged new tests on the
missile warheads unearthed in Iraq, which the U.S. army laboratory
alleged containing VX nerve gas.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to Iraqi Television Friday, advisor at the
Presidency Office Amir as-Saadi said Iraq demanded new tests be
done on these warhead fragments, and a scientific conference be
held attended by experts from neutral countries to analyze the
results.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post reported Tuesday that traces of VX nerve
agent were found in samples of Scud missiles warhead fragments
recovered in March from a destruction site at Nibai, north of
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The report was later confirmed by Richard Butler, Chairman of
the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating
weapons of mass destruction in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
As-Saadi said that the current allegation will be just like
previous ones released by Butler, which turned out to be false and
wrong.
</P>
<P>
"The fact is that VX was not weaponized in any kind of
ammunition," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also criticized the UNSCOM for leaking the alleged results
to media instead of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, As-Saadi stressed that Iraq will continue implementing
its commitments toward the UNSCOM on disarmament in Iraq, and will
not stop cooperating with it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
