<HEADLINE> S. Africa, France to Sign Trade Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and France will
sign five financial agreements worth 335 million Rand (about 60
million U.S. Dollars) during a coming three-day visit by French
President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
Chirac is due to arrive at Waterkloof Air Force Base outside
Pretoria Friday morning from Namibia for the second leg of a
six-day Southern African tour, local daily Sowetan reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela will meet Chirac at the
Union Buildings, where they will witness the signing of
agreements on police cooperation, sport and maritime transport.
</P>
<P>
In addition, two more bilateral treaties will be signed by
French and South African ministers later in the day.
</P>
<P>
Namibian sources reaching here said Chirac with a 50-strong
delegation of businessmen, arrived in Windhoek, the capital of
Namibia, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It was the first visit to the country by a serving French
president. The aim of the visit is believed to beef up French
commercial ties, and to expand its diplomatic influence in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, the French head of state said that Namibia,
with a population of just 1.6 million in an area three times the
size of France, was a democratic country where business could set
up in an atmosphere of stability and security.
</P>
<P>
There were a number of development projects of particular
interest to France, particularly agriculture and energy.
</P>
<P>
One in particular which could soon become a reality was a new
bridge over the Zambezi River on Namibia's extreme northeastern
border with Zambia which would open access to central and eastern
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Namibian President Sam Nujoma said earlier that his country,
rich in natural resources and minerals, could form a mutually
beneficial alliance with France through Chirac's visit.
</P>
<P>
Chirac will leave for Maputo, Mozambique on Sunday afternoon,
where he will spend 24 hours before visiting Angola to wind up
his southern African visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
