<HEADLINE> S. Africa's COSATU Vows Election Support for ANC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Congress of South
African Trade Unions (COSATU) has declared overwhelming support
for the African National Congress (ANC) in next year's general
election, media report here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
At its four-day inaugural central committee meeting ended
Thursday, COSATU endorsed last year's decision not to put up its
own list of candidates, with COSATU members in the government
appearing on an ANC ticket.
</P>
<P>
COSATU and the South African Communist Party (SACP) are in a
ruling alliance with the ANC.
</P>
<P>
COSATU proposed an ANC-COSATU-SACP alliance political council
to exercise final political authority on all issues relating to
the overall transformation of the state and the economy.
</P>
<P>
The federation decided to discuss with the government
extending the elections to two days, to ensure that people in
rural areas were able to vote.
</P>
<P>
The central committee, COSATU's highest decision-making body
between congresses, agreed that each COSATU member would
contribute one Rand to be used by the federation for election
purposes.
</P>
<P>
Union members would also pay a levy, which would be determined
by the federation at its central executive committee meeting, to
be donated to the ANC.
</P>
<P>
The unions would look for other source of finances, including
requests to the unions' investment companies.
</P>
<P>
COSATU resolved to develop a clear message aimed at advancing
its goal of a better life for all.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General Mbhazima Shilowa said COSATU needed to
release its members to go from door to door campaigning for
votes, and to ensure that prospective voters had their identity
documents and were registered for elections.
</P>
<P>
COSATU is opposed to government's Growth, Employment and
Redistribution macro-economic strategy, and has repeatedly
challenged government's labor retrenchment policy.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the week, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki urged COSATU
to ensure that the ANC was returned to power with an overwhelming
majority in next year's election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
