<HEADLINE> Troussier Still Wants to Coach South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Philippe Troussier said he still
wanted to coach the South African team if he was asked by the South
African Football Association (SAFA).
</P>
<P>
Troussier's contract with the SAFA ended with the team's World Cup
exit. But he said when arrived at Johannesburg:"I am one hundred
percent available to continue coaching Bafana Bafana and finish my
mission."
</P>
<P>
Troussier said he had received several other coaching
offers:"For the moment my future is open. I can take a job as
national coach of Saudi Arabia, Tunisia or stay with South Africa,
so I'm not concerned about my future."
</P>
<P>
SAFA president Molefi Oliphant said that Troussier's assistant
Trott Moloto had been named the caretaker-coach, "Philipe's contract
was only valid until after the World Cup, and has in fact expired.
But it is too early to respond to whether we'll appoint a new coach
or not." said Oliphant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
