<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China on Course to Sustainable Growth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- China is pushing ahead in a major
bid to achieve sustainable growth which will place the world's
most populous country on a path of sound social and economic
development in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The ambitious government program calls for China to earmark
massive funding to strengthen protection of the environment,
ecology and arable land, in addition to bolstering the economic
use of the natural resources, according to an official from the
State Development Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
China has pledged it will not sacrifice the environment,
resources and long-term welfare of the people in pursuit of
economic gain. Rapid economic growth will be based on
environmentally-sound environmental and energy efficient
approaches.
</P>
<P>
Environmental protection is placed at the top of China's
sustainable growth strategy, with investments in related efforts
expected to hit 180 billion yuan (21 billion US dollars) within
three years, according to Xie Zhenhua, director of the State
General Administration of Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
Immediate pollution control targets centers on three rivers --
Huaihe, Haihe and Liaohe, and three lakes -- Taihu, Chaohu and
Dianchi in Jiangsu, Anhui and Yunnan provinces, as well as the
capital city of Beijing. China is also carrying out a project to
control acid rain and sulfur dioxide on 1.09 million sq.km., or
11.4 percent of the nation's total land area.
</P>
<P>
China launched more than 700 afforestation projects as part of
its effort to establish a so-called green "Great Wall". The goal
of the program is to prevent soil erosion and ecological
deterioration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China on Course to Sustainable Growth (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Stringent measures have also been introduced to protect
valuable land resources needed to feed China's population of over
1.2 billion people. The government encourages farmers to practice
ecological farming which ensures the efficient use of land and
natural resources and offer good economic returns.
</P>
<P>
Construction sites have consumed vast stretches of China's
147 million ha of arable land at an alarming rate in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
China encourages the efficient use of energy during economic
development and attaches great importance to achieving
technological advancement which promotes the cost-effective use of
natural resources. Investments in technological transformation
projects are expected to top 170 billion yuan, and the
construction of nuclear power and hydropower projects is gaining
momentum.
</P>
<P>
Local leaders have gained a greater sense of the importance of
sustainable growth and more municipalities, provinces and
autonomous regions have increased spending on environmental
protection. Shanghai, the nation's largest industrial center,
alone plans to pump 70 billion yuan into environmental and
ecological protection projects by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Observers note that China, a developing country with low per
capita natural resources, faces an arduous task in promoting
coordinated economic and social growth. Nonetheless, they stress
that the long-terms benefits involved deserve relentless
efforts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Registering Religious Rendezvous Meaning No Limitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Ye Xiaowen, director of the State
Bureau of Religious Affairs, said here today that the Chinese
government requires the registration of religious organizations
and sites for religious activities in order to protect normal
religious activities and ensure the legitimate status of sites
for religious activities, rather than as a means of limiting
religious freedom.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at today's press conference hosted by the Information
Office of the State Council, Ye said it is the general practice in
many countries to require social organizations to register with
relevant government departments.
</P>
<P>
In China, the regulation covering the registration and
administration of all social organizations, including religious
organizations, requires such bodies to register with government
civil affairs departments, said Ye, adding that China has more
than 3,000 registered religious organizations.
</P>
<P>
He said Chinese religious believers account for about 10
percent of the total population, and noted that legal measures
must be used to effectively ensure their right to conduct normal
religious activities. Ye added that the registration system has
won support from the country's religious sector.
</P>
<P>
The registration of sites for religious activities has also
proceeded smoothly according to law since 1994, said Ye.
</P>
<P>
About 85,000 places of worship had registered with the
government in accordance with the State Council's Regulations on
the Administration of Sites for Religious Activities by the end of
last year.
</P>
<P>
Ye pointed out that concerned government departments fully
respect the characteristics of various religious beliefs during
the registration process.
</P>
<P>
For example there are no registration requirements for what
Chinese Christians refer to as "home services", or religious
activities which relatives and friends attend to pray and study
the Bible. Ye stressed that the government in no way interferes
with or limits normal activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
