<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US President Clinton Tours Xi'an (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton
spent the first day of his nine-day state trip in Xi'an today, to
view famous terra-cotta warriors in a museum named after the
warriors in an outskirtan Lintong city and talking to local
residents at an adjacent village.
</P>
<P>
Now the capital city of the northwestern Shaanxi Province,
Xi'an had served as the imperial capital for 12 ancient Chinese
dynasties.
</P>
<P>
At noon today, President Clinton and his wife Hillary arrived
at the museum of life-size terra-cotta warriors in the company of
Shaanxi Provincial Governor Cheng Andong and his wife, and Curator
Wu Yongqi of the museum.
</P>
<P>
Unearthed in the late 1970s from the Mausoleum of the First
Emperor of the Qin Dynasty (221-207 B.C.), the terra-cotta
warriors are known as the "Eighth Wonder of the World".
</P>
<P>
The Clintons were first escorted into the No.1 vault, at the
platform of which Wu, the curator, briefed them on the work
concerning the excavation, restoration and protection of the
terra-cotta army.
</P>
<P>
The Clintons then descended to the basement of the army vault
and looked closely at the warriors with great interest, inquiring
about the material used and craftsmanship adopted in the making of
these warriors.
</P>
<P>
Wu answered all the questions the distinguished guests asked.
</P>
<P>
The Clintons posed among the terra-cotta warriors repeatedly
for cameramen to take pictures.
</P>
<P>
In No.1 Army Vault there are formations of more than 6,000
chariot soldiers and infantry troopers.
</P>
<P>
Then, the Clintons procceeded to visit the terra-cotta warriors
restoration center and the No. 2 Vault, where they viewed and
appreciated unearthed rare bronze chariots and horses.
</P>
<P>
In the afternoon, President Clinton and his official delegation
visited the Shaanxi Museum of History, which shows the
longstanding history of Shaanxi, invaluable cultural relics and
treasure frescos from the Tang Dynasty (618-907).
</P>
<P>
Boasting more than 370,000 items of rare cultural relics
unearthed in Shaanxi, the Shaanxi Museum of History is China's
first enormous national-level museum with state-of-art facilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
