<HEADLINE> President Clinton Tours Xi'an (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Earlier, President Clinton and his wife Hillary visited the
Xiahe Village on the outskirts of Xi'an this morning.
</P>
<P>
With its 1,300-plus people, the village just about one
kilometer away from the site of the terra-cotta warriors, has been
turned an affluent one thanks to its service to tourists visiting
the site of relics.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent of its villagers' incomes have derived
from local tourist industry, and the village has been cited as one
of Shaanxi's model well-to-do villages.
</P>
<P>
At ten o'clock this morning, the Clintons arrived at the Xiahe
Village, where they were met by village head Yang Yunlong and
other locals at the village entrance.
</P>
<P>
They first had a 40-minute talk with six people under the
foliage of a tree in front the court of a farmer's household.
Among the local participants at the talk are a farmer, a primary
school teacher, a restaurant manager and a college student.
</P>
<P>
Addressing on the topic of "China's Changes and I", the
participants answered questions raised by Clinton and his wife.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a brief speech at the village primary school,
President Clinton said he had learned that local farmers have
adopted to the advanced farming techniques and so they can spend
more time on traveling, making arts and crafts and engage in other
trades.
</P>
<P>
He said he was pleased to see that the villagers now have TV
sets and telephones and set up a primary school, and the life of
the villagers has been improved as people elsewhere in China.
</P>
<P>
Clinton wished the village a still brighter future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
