<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Full-Time Farm Workers on Drop in EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Full-time agricultural workers
decreased by 125,000 people, or 1.8 percent, on European Union
(EU) farms last year, Eurostat said Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, said the Luxembourg-based statistical office of the
European communities, the fall was less than the longer-term trend.
</P>
<P>
Earlier figures show that average annual fall in the EU's
agricultural labor volume was 3.8 percent between 1986 and 1991,
and 4.0 percent between 1991 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
From 1979 to 1997, the number of agricultural full-time labor
equivalents fell from an estimated 12.6 million to 6.9 million.
</P>
<P>
The falling trend of full-time farm workers was mainly
attributed to the falls in France and Italy, where the labor
volume was down 2.5 percent and 1.4 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Italy accounts for one fourth of the total EU agricultural
labor volume while France accounts for 15 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Farm worker decrease was also witnessed in Germany, Greece,
Spain and Portugal that combine to account for another 40 percent
of the EU agricultural labor volume. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
