<HEADLINE> French President Visits S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques
Chirac arrived in South Africa Friday for a three-day state
visit.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela hailed Chirac as an old
friend, saying Chirac's current visit, the first of its kind, to
South Africa will strengthen their bonds.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said at a joint news briefing after talks with Chirac
that France was the first European country he visited after his
release from prison.
</P>
<P>
"I have known President Chirac when he was mayor of Paris.
Every time I went to France, I also saw Chirac."
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he did not view Chirac's southern African trip as
a departure from France's involvement with its former colonies in
west Africa.
</P>
<P>
"I would not talk of departure, but of continuation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chirac's four-nation southern African tour comes less than a
year after France introduced changes in its Africa policies, away
from involvement in its former African colonies.
</P>
<P>
The new policy recognizes that South Africa has become a
cornerstone for new investment and growth in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said France's long-standing relations with western
African countries would not change, but it was important for it
to also strive for relations of friendship, partnership and trust
with the countries of southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
"This will start with South Africa, which is the real engine
for the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about progress in trade talks between South Africa and
the European Union, Chirac said the negotiations were drawing to
a close.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that a free trade agreement would be
reached before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in South Africa, Chirac is scheduled to meet
South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, National Assembly
Speaker Frene Ginwala as well as other officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
