<HEADLINE> Chinese Economists Say That Stabilizing The RMB Is The Right Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Tang Min of the Asian Development
Bank and Zuo Xiaolei of the Philippines' Asian Administration
College say in today's "Economic Daily" that a depreciation of the
yuan would quite likely spark a round of depreciation of other
currencies in Asia and that stabilization of the Chinese currency
is the best choice.
</P>
<P>
Since last July, the currencies in Asian countries have
depreciated by 40 to 70 percent against the U.S. dollar during the
financial crisis, producing a bad effect on China's economic
development, especially on its exports.
</P>
<P>
Exports of most of these countries have declined instead of
increased after the devaluation, so China may not get the effect
of enhancing competitiveness on the international market even if
it really depreciates the renminbi, Tang and Zuo, both Chinese
working overseas, say.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, a stable rmb will help safeguard economic
and financial stability in Hong Kong which is essential to
maintaining exports, attracting more overseas investment and
making better use of international finance.
</P>
<P>
They say that Hong Kong's prosperity and stability are an
important way to sustain economic development in China's interior,
so aid to Hong Kong is aid for the interior.
</P>
<P>
A stable rmb will also help maintain overseas investors'
confidence in China, so that maintaining a stable rmb is China's
contribution to the Asian economy and it is in China's own
economic interest because it hopes to have an eight percent growth
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
