<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "One Country, Two Systems" Not Applicable to Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Ye Xiaowen, director of the
State Council's Bureau of Religious Affairs, said at a
news conference today that the "one country, two systems"
principle is being used to resolve the Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan
issues, but cannot be applied to Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Tibet was peacefully liberated in 1951 and completed democratic
reform in 1959 and has had regional autonomy like other ethnic
minority areas in China since then, Ye said, and the principle
does not fit there.
</P>
<P>
The Dalai Lama has claimed that he would no longer seek Tibet
independence, but that Tibet should have a "high degree of
autonomy". In reply, Ye points out that the Dalai Lama has
actually switched to a two-step process for Tibetan independence.
</P>
<P>
The first step is a "high degree of autonomy", through which he
could restore control over over Tibet, and the second is Tibetan
independence, or what he calls "a political system edging up
towards independence."
</P>
<P>
Ye pointed to the many cruelties Tibetans suffered under the
serf system and said that only after serfdom was abolished, did
the Tibetan people begin to enjoy the political rights guaranteed
by the Constitution and the regional autonomy of ethnic minorities
law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
