<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Protects Normal Religious Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese citizens enjoy full rights
to freedom of religious belief, according to Ye Xiaowen, director
of the State Bureau of Religious Affairs.
</P>
<P>
"Religious believers are free to participate all normal
religious activities in temples, mosques, churches or homes,"
said Ye.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that enjoying the right to freedom of religious
belief, citizens must also carry out duties prescribed by law.
</P>
<P>
"A handful of religious believers in China have been punished
for their illegal activities or crimes in recent years, and the
punishment of criminals in accordance with the law has absolutely
nothing to do with religious belief."
</P>
<P>
Ye told a press conference here today, "the Chinese government
maintains that every country should respect the characteristics of
other countries and promote mutual understanding through dialogue,
while opposing any interference in the internal affairs of other
nations under the pretext of religion".
</P>
<P>
Ye noted that about 10 percent of China's total population
belongs to various religions, including Buddhism, Taoism, Islam,
Catholicism and Protestantism.
</P>
<P>
The nation's over 85,000 places of worship are staffed by over
300,000 religious personnel. China is home to 3,000 national and
local religious organizations and 74 seminaries which have
graduated more than 5,000 students and have current enrollments
totalling 4,000 students.
</P>
<P>
"Religious believers enjoy the same political rights as people
from other walks of life," said Ye.
</P>
<P>
He noted that some 17,000 religious personnel serve either as
deputies to people's congresses or committee members of political
consultative conferences at various levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. President Clinton Arrives in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and
Mrs. Hillary Clinton arrived in Beijing at 8:20 (local time) this
evening to continue his nine-day state visit to China.
</P>
<P>
The president flew in here from the ancient northwest city of
Xi'an, the first stop of his China trip.
</P>
<P>
As the U.S. President and Mrs. Clinton alighted from the
presidential plane at 8:34 p.m. local time (12:34 GMT), they were
greeted by Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao and his wife Liu
Yongqing, Chinese Ambassador to the United States Li Zhaoxing and
his wife, and Vice-Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi. Then, two
girls presented bouquets of flowers to the Presidential couple.
</P>
<P>
Principal members of President Clinton's official delegation
include U.S. Ambassador to China James Sasser, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, Secretary of Treasury Robert Rubin, Secretary
of Agriculture Daniel Glickman, Secretary of Commerce William
Daley, Chairman of the Council of Economic Advisors Janet Yellen,
Ambassador Charlene Barshefsky, Director of the Office of the
President Erskine Bowles, Assistant to the President for National
Security Affairs Samuel Berger, Counselor to the President Doug
Sosnik, and senators, House representatives and other White House
officials and cabinet members.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton's motorcade moved from the airport by Press
time, and is heading for the Diaoyutai State Guesthouse about 35
km from the airport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
