<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, US See Increasing Legal Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- China's Minister of Justice Gao
Changli told Xinhua today that the cooperation in law between
China and the United States is growing and said that efforts to
increase exchanges and cooperation will continue.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have cooperated extensively in the education
of law, he said, and, since 1986, the East China University of
Political Science and Law and American universities have had a
training program on China's legal system that has trained more
than 700 American lawyers and law students.
</P>
<P>
China has invited 200 legal scholars from the United States to
lecture in China in the past decade and Chinese universities have
established ties with about 20 American law schools.
</P>
<P>
A graduate program will be started next year by the China
University of Political Science and Law and the U.S.'s Temple
University, granting degrees for students upon graduation.
</P>
<P>
Gao said that the China-U.S. symposium on economic law in China
in 1987 had several hundred lawyers, bankers, and business people
from the United States and started cooperation between the two
countries' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
He says that Chinese and American lawyers have cooperated
extensively in stocks, fund raising, domestic and overseas
investment, intellectual property rights, marine business, and
protecting the rights of Chinese and American citizens and legal
persons, and that 21 American Law firms have set up offices in
major Chinese cities like Beijing, Guangzhou, Shanghai, Haikou,
and Qingdao, and 5 Chinese law firms have offices in New York,
Chicago, Washington D.C., and Seattle.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
