<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Expert Helps Reclaim Chinese Desert Into Oasis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Seiei Tohyama, a Japanese expert
who is presiding over a Chinese reclamation project, has expressed
his confidence that "people are able to turn a desert into an
oasis."
</P>
<P>
The 92-year-old Japanese agriculturist who specializes in
desert reclamation has taken the challenge of the incurable
"cancer on earth" -- the Kubch Desert in the Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region in north China.
</P>
<P>
He said ambitiously that he will turn the Kubch Desert into an
oasis on which 200,000 people at least will be able reside.
</P>
<P>
Tohyama began his desert reclamation work in 1990 in Engbey,
located in the recesses of the Kubch Desert, with a Chinese
businessman named Wang Haiming.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese expert, who had successfully reclaimed 420,000
hectares of desert in Japan, said the 21st century will be a epoch
of desert development, and that it is vital for humans to handle
desert reclamation programs well .
</P>
<P>
With painstaking effort in the past eight years, two million
trees have been planted in Engbey, 100,000 hectares of grassland
cleared; and two reservoirs built.
</P>
<P>
Wang Haiming, who is director of the desert development
exemplary zone of Engbey, said afforestation is just the basis of
their comprehensive development plan, and that their ultimate aim
is to develop a multi-industry chain on the desert.
</P>
<P>
Engbey has more than 2,000 head of fine goats that are bred by
Xu Gorigan, a scientist of Mongolian nationality. The goats yield
an annual output worth nearly 1 million yuan (120,000
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Engbey called back the ostrich that lived on
the Kubch Desert 30,000 years ago, and invited the 47 peafowl from
south China. An ostrich eggshell sells for as much as 300 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Besides growing grain, vegetables and herbs, the Engbey
developers have imported and planted flower seeds from Japan, and
they expect to profit from selling the reproduced flower seeds
back to Japan.
</P>
<P>
The farming industry has been basically mechanized in Engbey
and advanced agricultural techniques have been introduced there.
</P>
<P>
To make full use of the tourist resources in Engbey -- such as
sand, forests and animals -- the developers formed a tour company
and built hotels several years ago, said Wang, adding that Engbey
receives nearly 10,000 tourists each year.
</P>
<P>
The desert lacks water, but a mineral water factory was
established in the Engbey development zone. Its product sells well
in cities nearby.
</P>
<P>
Several research institutes in the country are now carrying out
cooperative programs to develop farming and animal-raising
techniques in Engbey, said Wang, adding that an electronic company
and a motor company of Japan intend to develop
solar-energy-powered automobile there.
</P>
<P>
"If there is enough funding, we can build Engbey into a Silicon
Valley of farming and animal-raising in China," Wang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
