<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: SAR Officials Impressed by Practice of "One Country, Two Systems" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- As the first anniversary of the
Special Administrative Region's (SAR) inauguration is approaching,
senior SAR government officials wrote articles or gave
interviews, speaking of what they have felt and what they have
done during the year.
</P>
<P>
These articles and interviews were carried Friday in a
four-page special column on Wen Wei Po, a major Chinese newspaper
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang in his article said that Hong
Kong's development during the past year fully accorded with what
the Basic Law stipulates, that is, Hong Kong people governing Hong
Kong with a high degree of autonomy. "This is an obvious fact for
all to see," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong residents are also deeply impressed by the fact that
the country will support and encourage us, if required, but will
never interfere, said Tsang.
</P>
<P>
"The relationship of mutual trust can help us develop a sense
of belonging toward our country," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong's economy has been battered by the
regional financial turmoil since August last year and it is
inevitable that Hong Kong will go through a period of adjustment.
</P>
<P>
"We Hong Kong people still have to face some tough days ahead
until we can see the light at the end of the tunnel," he remarked.
He also made it clear that the SAR government will overcome the
adversities along with the Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the successful practice of "one country, two
systems" in Hong Kong, Secretary for Electoral Affairs Michael
Suen said in an interview: "Time has proved everything."
</P>
<P>
Before the handover, there had been concern about interference
from the Central People's Government in Hong Kong's affairs. But
what took place in the past year fully demonstrated that the
promises of "one country, two systems" and "Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong" have been put into practice in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
According to Lily Yam, commissioner of the Independent
Commission Against Corruption (ICAC), the ICAC has continued its
dependent and effective work against corruption since July 1,
1997.
</P>
<P>
The confidence of Hong Kong people in ICAC has been maintained
at a very high level, while various regional and international
surveys still ranking Hong Kong as one of the most cleanest cities
in Asia, Yam said.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for the Civil Service Lam Woon-kwong said, as a
senior civil servant, he has a deep impression about the
implementation of "one country, two systems" in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
One example is that expatriate civil servants in the SAR
government obtained approval from the Central People's Government
to attend international meetings as members of the Chinese
delegation. The pragmatic approach demonstrated the country's
determination to safeguard Hong Kong's long-term interests, Lam
said.
</P>
<P>
He referred to the improvement brought up since the handover in
two aspects: one is that there is no longer time and space
limitations in formulating policies, the other is that
cross-border cooperation is becoming institutionalized.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner of Customs and Excise Lawrence Li Shu-fai said,
Hong Kong remains a separate customs area after the handover and
his work is basically unchanged except for more frequent use of
the Chinese language.
</P>
<P>
As a Hong Kong Chinese, it's a pleasant thing to work for the
SAR government of China, Li said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
