<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Music Continues After Handover for Chan by Wang Qun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Here in Hong Kong, a dynamic and
diverse metropolis, everyone has his or her way of life. For Chan
Yim-pao, bread earner of a family of four, Chiu Chow music is
his way of life.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all of his leisure time is devoted to Chiu Chow music, a
branch of traditional Chinese music which is not so popular in the
city.
</P>
<P>
In the words of his teenage daughter Chan Hei, "My father is
just crazy about that music."
</P>
<P>
Chan, 44, was first fascinated by the beauty of Chiu Chow music
when he was very young. At his hometown, a tiny fishing village
on the coast of Fujian Province, he used to play the music with
friends at a store for self-entertainment. "Those happy days are
kept deep in my memory," Chan said.
</P>
<P>
He settled down in Hong Kong in 1983 and founded a label
company in 1989 with some 30,000 HK dollars (nearly 4,000 U.S.
dollars). The mini-company with two machines is located in his
flat in the old industrial district of Kwun Tong, Kowloon, and
Chan is the only worker. The company's good record of fast
delivery of products earns it a few committed customers.
</P>
<P>
Chan could never forget the early days of his company. At that
time, he and his wife were still working in a carton factory. They
made the best use of every minute of lunch time to call on garment
manufacturers based in Kwun Tong, sending out name cards and
waiting for response.
</P>
<P>
Finally came orders. "I worked at night. Sometimes I had to
work overnight to finish it. The second day I still went to the
carton factory," Chan recalled.
</P>
<P>
Nearly round-the-clock work left no time to music. Fortunately
their business got on the track very soon. Chan and his wife left
the cartoon factory, putting all the energy on their small
undertaking.
</P>
<P>
And Chan picked up erxian string, his favorite instrument in
Chiu Chow music, again. Every morning, he gets up early and does
a one-hour solo at home; when night falls, he goes out to play
with partners.
</P>
<P>
He was proud of his band, grouping "top players" in Hong Kong.
"In the run-up to the handover last year, British Broadcasting
Corporation visited our playing venue at Sheung Wan, shooting the
scene for a program about life in Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
Now one year has passed. As an immigrant who has been well
integrated into the Hong Kong community, Chan said he noticed no
significant change in his life since that specific date.
</P>
<P>
"Even before the handover, I had never worried much about it,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"It's very natural for Hong Kong to return to her motherland,"
said Chan, who returns to his hometown "at least three times a
year" for traditional Chinese festivals.
</P>
<P>
For Chan, life continues, music continues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
