<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Hong Kong Family Tied With Putonghua by Chang Kefei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Life is as usual for the Sin
family nearly one year after the handover on July 1, 1997, when
Hong Kong reverted from British rule to become a special
administrative region (SAR) of China.
</P>
<P>
Sin Kam Wai, husband and father of the family, continues to
teach Chinese at a secondary school -- a stable and well-paid job,
especially in the economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
His wife Susan So, a welfare worker, still takes care of a
"small group home", which has eight children in need of parental
care.
</P>
<P>
Their two daughters Fong and Annie, both in the early 20s, go
on with their study at college in New Zealand, and fly back to
Hong Kong every year for summer vocation.
</P>
<P>
The husband and wife said that there was nothing different with
their life and work after the handover. "Almost everything is the
same," they said, "except that more and more people begin to learn
Putonghua."
</P>
<P>
Sin is also principal of Hong Kong Putonghua Society, a
non-government, non-profit organization devoted to the promotion
of Putonghua, the standard spoken Chinese. For the last two
decades, he has seen a burgeoning Hong Kong population, who
usually speak English and Cantonese, learn Putonghua.
</P>
<P>
The society now enrolls about 20,000 students a year, while it
only took several hundred per year in the early days. Sin
explained that the "Putonghua heat" was fueled by close economic
intersection and frequent personal exchange between the mainland
and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Susan added that Hong Kong schools now open Putonghua courses
for students at lower grades and increase the number of courses
per week.
</P>
<P>
She said that the eight children she looks after all take
Putonghua lessons at school.
</P>
<P>
Susan has been playing the role of "mother" at the "small group
home" for three years, and accordingly her husband acts as the
"father". They live together with the four boys and four girls,
aged between 6 and 17, who lack parental care due to family
problems or mental handicap. Their home is one of the 12 sponsored
by the International Social Service Hong Kong Branch.
</P>
<P>
Susan, who used to be a kindergarten teacher, told Xinhua: "We
try to provide them with a normal family, and establish a sense of
trust with them."
</P>
<P>
"It is a challenging work that need love and patience, but it
is truly rewarding when I see them regard me as their mother and
let me know everything about themselves," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I love kids, and I hope they can all grow up to be good and
healthy persons," said Susan, who took up the job three years ago
when her daughters went to college in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
"My daughters were surprised to find that they could use
Putonghua on the foreign land, to communicate with their Chinese
classmates from Malaysia and Taiwan," said Sin, who encouraged
them to learn Putonghua in childhood. Fong and Annie now speak
fluent Putonghua, Cantonese and English.
</P>
<P>
During the Christmas last year, the Sin family traveled to
Beijing and were impressed with many places of interest. "We want
our children to know more about the Chinese people, the culture
and the language," said Sin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
