<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Using Donations To Help Handicapped People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The China Welfare Fund for the
Handicapped, China's leading foundation of its kind, has said that
domestic and overseas donations for disabled people are being used
properly.
</P>
<P>
Chinese and overseas organizations and individuals gave 6.6
million yuan (800,000 US dollars) last year, which became part of
the foundation's 1997 budget of 10.59 million yuan for welfare
work for the handicapped, the foundation reported today.
</P>
<P>
More aid has come in the form of cooperative programs. Lions
Club, the worldwide charitable organization, for example, financed
cataract operations. These programs used an estimated 20 million
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The foundation allocated large sums for paying the interest on
loans to handicapped people for starting businesses, and to create
employment, education, and rehabilitation opportunities.
</P>
<P>
About 50,000 disabled people found jobs, more than 60,000
received rehabilitation training, and 350,000 cataract patients
had their eyesight restored through operations last year.
</P>
<P>
China has at least 1,500 schools for handicapped children.
Over 60 percent of the enrolled are handicapped children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
