<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Newspapers Welcome Clinton's Visit to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong newspapers published
commentaries Friday, welcoming U.S. President Bill Clinton's first
state visit to China starting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ming Pao Daily News, in a commentary entitled "Sino-U.S.
cooperation benefits the whole world", said this forthcoming
summit, closely following Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit to
the U.S. last October, is a clear indication that the Sino-U.S.
relations are developing and improving, which is beneficial to the
efforts of Asia and the world as a whole to move into the next
millennium in a stable and peaceful fashion.
</P>
<P>
A commentary published by Hong Kong Economic Times said Clinton
brought some concrete gifts for his China tour, such as relaxing
restrictions on U.S. high-tech exports to China and a proposal for
granting China the permanent Most-Favored-Nation status. In
return, China has prepared for the guest a large number of orders
for U.S. aircraft and telecommunications products.
</P>
<P>
However, the paper stressed, the greatest significance and
achievement of the visit will not be these agreements or
contracts, but the visit itself.
</P>
<P>
The visit will be a new landmark in the Sino-U.S. relationship,
marking that their links have entered a new phase based on
understanding and cooperation, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Commercial Daily hailed Clinton's trip as a visit
promoting friendship between the Chinese people and the American
people.
</P>
<P>
There is no denying the fact that the two countries have
differences over many issues, such as human rights and religion,
due to different cultures, history and social systems. However,
what they share in common far exceeds what their differ in.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' recent cooperation in dealing with the Asian
financial turmoil fully demonstrates that their cooperation not
only accords with the interests of the two countries, but also
benefits the stability and development of Asia and the world, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
Entitled "Global future in their hands", an editorial of Hong
Kong Standard, a major English newspaper in Hong Kong, said that
Clinton pointedly referred to two of the vital matters which
"affect not merely Sino-U.S. relations but also the peace and
security of Asia" -- the Korean peninsula and South Asia -- in his
speech soon after arriving in the ancient city of Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
"Not referred to but almost certainly to be taken up when Mr.
Clinton meets Mr. Jiang in Beijing will be the regional financial
crisis and the stability of the Japanese yen, both of which are
playing havoc with the economies of Asia, including Hong Kong,"
said Hong Kong Standard.
</P>
<P>
"These are matters the two leaders must focus on at their
summit; all other issues can be taken up later as Sino-U.S. ties
broaden and deepen. Between friends controversial matters can be
taken up without adversarial overtones; when that stage arrives
many of those issues that now divide will no longer be obstacles
to progress," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The summit "is not just about how these two powerful countries
will relate to each other in the new century, but also what sort
of world they will create for the new millennium," the paper
concluded.
</P>
<P>
Wen Wei Po's Thursday commentary observed that economic and
trade cooperation between China and the United States will do good
to Hong Kong economy, since Hong Kong acts as an entrepot for some
60 percent of Sino-U.S. trade. Besides, the U.S. is Hong Kong's
second largest export market and a major investor in Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
