<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Looking For Land Use Rights Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A people's deputy today asked
China's top legislature, the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress (NPC), to pass a law protecting farmers' land
use rights.
</P>
<P>
Xu Xingguan, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the
Zhejiang Province People's Congress, said that even though 50-year
contracts for land have been signed by local governments and
farmers all over the country, farmers are still worried about
changes taking place in land policy and are looking for protection
of their land under the law.
</P>
<P>
Xu told today's NPC Standing Committee meeting that
acknowledging the importance of land to farmers during China's
rural reforms and the household responsibility contract system,
which allows farmers long-term rights to land use are crucial and
that some local businesses and institutions have taken over
farmers' land in the name of "public interest", and that many
township enterprises have built factories on farmland without
getting farmers' permission.
</P>
<P>
There should be revisions in the land use law to protect
farmers' rights, Xu said, suggesting that special protection be
given through a national land use plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
