<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspended Particles, Major Air Problem In Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The major air pollution problem
last week of Chinese cities is total suspended particles (TSP),
the China Environment Monitoring Center (CEMC) said today.
</P>
<P>
Of the 45 major cities covered by CEMC's weekly air quality
report, 39 had a problem with TSP mainly caused by the burning of
coal, construction work, and road dust.
</P>
<P>
In the June 19-25 period, the cities of Shantou, Guilin,
Fuzhou, Nanning, Zhanjiang, Nanchang, Ningbo, Zhuhai, Beihai, and
Haikou had excellent air quality.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-six, including Guangzhou, Shanghai, Nanjing and Suzhou,
had good air quality, while Beijing, Tianjin and Xi'an were among
the 9 cities with slight air pollution.
</P>
<P>
The major problem of Shanghai, Guangzhou, Shenzhen and Xiamen
was nitrogen oxide, mainly caused by automobile exhaust, and the
problem in Chongqing and Changsha was sulfur dioxide, mainly from
burning coal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
