<HEADLINE> President Clinton Leaves Xi'an For Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton
concluded his visit to this ancient city this afternoon and left
here for Beijing by his presidential plane early this evening.
</P>
<P>
The US president flew in here Thursday evening, starting his
nine-day state visit to China.
</P>
<P>
The Xi'an City Government hosted for President Clinton, his
wife Hillary and his official delegation a grand welcome ceremony
that revives an ancient parade ritual in honor of distinguished
</P>
<P>
During their stay in Xi'an, capital of a dozen ancient
dynasties and of today's Shaanxi Province, the president and his wife
visited the Old City Wall, the terra-cotta warriors unearthed from
the mausoleum of the first emperor of Qin Dynasty (221-207 BC)
and the Shaanxi Museum of History.
</P>
<P>
They also paid a visit to the Xiahe Village some one km away
from the site of the terra-cotta warriors, where they had a
40-minute discussion with villagers. The president also made a
brief speech at the village primary school.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton and Shaanxi Governor Cheng Andong had a
cordial meeting at noon.
</P>
<P>
Vice Governor of Shaanxi Jia Zhibang and his wife, Xi'an Mayor
Feng Xuchu saw the U.S. President and his official delegation off
at the airport.  
</P>
</TEXT>
