<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Getting More Handicapped People Away From Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Deng Pufang, the chairman of China
Disabled Persons' Federation (CDPF), China's major organization
for the handicapped, announced today that CDPF will help three
million disabled people living in poverty get adequate food and
clothing this year.
</P>
<P>
Helping them get away from poverty must be the most important
assistance for the handicapped and a key to the country's
poverty-elimination efforts, he said. This is intended to be a
major blow against poverty, something that is vital to 17 million
handicapped people, or about 30 percent of the total number of
handicapped in China.
</P>
<P>
The Federation joined the State Council, the Ministry of
Finance, and the People's Bank of China in April in announcing
that all handicapped people living in poverty will have adequate
food and clothing by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
They will encourage handicapped people to make money with
businesses, breeding livestock or poultry, or making
handicrafts. Funds and technical training will be provided by the
government and organizations.
</P>
<P>
"Most of them can work and become prosperous. But they are
often ignored and can't get help because of physical deformities,"
Deng explained. China's central and local governments provided
more than 200 million yuan in special loans last year to help 1.08
million handicapped people get away from poverty, he told a
meeting of the executive council of the China Welfare Fund for the
Handicapped, of which he is chairman.
</P>
<P>
About 50,000 disabled people got jobs and more than 70,000
started their own businesses last year, Deng said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Frees 60 Lebanese Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Israel handed over 60 Lebanese
prisoners Friday to Lebanon through the International Committee
for the Red Cross (ICRC) as a part of the swap of prisoners and
body parts between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
At midday, leaders of the country's anti-Israeli Shiite Muslim
groups went to the Kfar Falous crossing near Lebanon's southern
biggest city of Sidon, which links the Israeli occupied-zone in
south Lebanon and the rest of the country, and officially took
delivery of the freed prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The freed detainees, most from the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or
Party of God, were bused to Beirut by the ICRC.
</P>
<P>
The swap, the second between Hezbollah and Israel in two years,
includes the exchange of the body parts of Israeli sergeant Itamar
Iliya for 40 bodies of Lebanese guerrillas and the release of the
60 Lebanese prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The remains, not including the scalp, of Iliya and 40 bodies of
Lebanese guerrillas were exchanged on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Iliya was one of the 12 Israeli soldiers killed in a botched
Israeli commando raid on the Lebanese southern village of
Insariyeh last September.
</P>
<P>
Most of his body parts were held by Hezbollah and Amal is
holding his scalp.
</P>
<P>
Amal refused to hand back the scalp as the group disagreed with
Israel over the number and names of the prisoners to be released.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that a mass funeral procession will be held for
the 40 killed guerrillas within days at the Great Prophet mosque
in the capital's southern suburbs, a stronghold of Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon since 1985 with the claimed aim to protect its northern
areas from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah is spearheading a war against Israeli occupation
forces and their allied South Lebanon Army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
