<HEADLINE> Tokyo Share Prices Continue Rising on Bank Merger News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed higher for the
third consecutive day in Tokyo Friday as the afternoon news report
that the struggling Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan (LTCB) would
merge with Sumitomo Trust and Banking Co. revitalized the market
at the last minute of the day's session.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 77.82 points, or 0.51
percent, from Thursday's close to finish at 15,210.04.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, gained 5.29 points or 0.45 percent to
1,190.82.
</P>
<P>
A Japanese business daily reported in its evening edition that
LTCB and Sumitomo Trust have agreed to merge their operations
possibly by next April.
</P>
<P>
The news is meaningful in terms of easing immediate fears about
Japan's financial system, an analyst at a private financial
institution said.
</P>
<P>
However, traders said that the merger, even if it becomes
formalized, would not erase the problem of how to deal with the
loads of bad loans which are hampering Japanese banks.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,334 issues listed on the First Section, losers
exceeded gainers 569 to 531 despite the Nikkei's rise, with 152
issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, on the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar,
which temporarily climbed above 143 yen level, retreated to below
142 yen on the bank merger news.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was quoted at 141.27-30 yen at 5 p.m., down
from 142.43-45 yen at 9 a.m., and from 142.15-25 yen late Thursday
in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
