<HEADLINE> U.S. President Visits Museum of Terra-cotta Warriors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and his
wife Hillary visited the museum of life-size terra-cotta warriors
here today in the company of Shaanxi Provincial Governor Cheng
Andong and his wife and museum Curator Wu Yongqi.
</P>
<P>
The US president and his wife were ushered into the No.1 vault
of terra-cotta warriors unearthed in the late 1970s in the
Mausoleum of the First Emperor of Qin Dynasty (221-207 BC).
</P>
<P>
At the platform of the vault, the curator told the guests the
excavation, restoration and protection of the terra-cotta
warriors, known as the "Eighth Wonder of the World."
</P>
<P>
The Clintons then walked down to the floor of the vault and
observed the warriors closely, inquiring about the material and
craftsmanship in the making of these warriors.
</P>
<P>
Wu Yongqi all the questions the guests asked.
</P>
<P>
Meeting the request of journalists, the Clintons posed among
the terra-cotta warriors time and again for cameramen to take
pictures.
</P>
<P>
In No.1 Vault are formations of more than 6,000 chariot
soldiers and infantry troops.
</P>
<P>
Then, the Clintons went to the terra-cotta warriors restoration
center and the No. 2 Vault, and inspected unearthed rare bronze
chariots and horses.
</P>
<P>
On the visitors' book of the museum, the U.S. president wrote:
"Thank you for a wonderful tour." and signed his name.
</P>
<P>
In the afternoon, Clinton and his official delegation visited
the Shaanxi Museum of History, which shows the long history of
Shaanxi, ancient cultural relics and treasure frescos from the
Tang Dynasty (618-907).
</P>
<P>
Boasting more than 370,000 items of rare cultural relics
unearthed in Shaanxi, the museum of history is China's first
enormous national-level museum with modern facilities.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the visit, Clinton wrote on the visitors' book:
"Thank you for sharing your treasures with us." 
</P>
</TEXT>
