<HEADLINE> 18 Drug Dealers Sentenced To Death In Southwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen people found guilty of
drug dealing were sentenced to death in Kunming, the capital of
Yunnan Province in southwestern China.
</P>
<P>
One of them, Li Guogao, had smuggled 3.49 kg of heroin, and
another, Lian Guangjin, had sold 5.2 kg of drugs, according to
local sources.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan's 4,000-km. border runs along part of the notorious
"golden triangle", and since the 1980s, it has been a major
conduit in international drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
During the early 1990s, Yunnan discovered that it had more than
57,000 drug users, the greatest number of all Chinese provinces
and autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
The province has dealt with 30,000 drug-related criminal cases
in the past seven years and confiscated 25,000 kg of drugs, or 80
percent of the nation's total of intercepted drugs. The number of
drug addicts in the province has been dropping steadily, thanks to
its anti-drug efforts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
