<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Economic Growth Slows Down in Six Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 26 (Xinhua)-- The economic growth rate in Vietnam
in the first six months of this year was officially estimated at
6.6 percent, lower than the planned target of 9 percent, according
to the Vietnam Economic Times Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Times quoted the General Statistics Administration as
saying that Vietnam's industry production grew by 12.6 percent,
agricultural production up about 2 percent, and state budget
revenue, 4.5 percent, as compared with last year's corresponding
period.
</P>
<P>
The country's export in the period valued at 4.56 billion
U.S. dollars, which was 9.3 percent up from that of the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese officials attributed the slowdown of economic growth
to the natural disasters the country is facing and the current
financial crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"Over the first six months of the year, Vietnam has coped with
great difficulties caused by fierce natural disasters and adverse
impacts of the on-going financial crisis in the region," Minister
of Planning and Investment Tran Xuan Gia told a conference earlier
this week to review the socio-economic situation.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Prime Minister Phan Van Khai also asked the
officials attending the conference to discuss measures to overcome
all difficulties and challenges, further promote the process of
institutional renewal, resolutely practice thrifty, and flexibly
manage macro-economy in order to prevent possible decline in
socio-economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
