<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Compensated For Damage Caused By Tiger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Four farmers in China's Jilin
Province were paid 1,000 yuan (120 U.S. dollars) each in
compensation by the local government for cows that were eaten by a
Siberian tiger in the Changbai Mountains earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Three of the four filed a lawsuit against the local government
last month demanding compensation for three cows eaten by a wild
male tiger, and they all say they are satisfied with the local
government's decision in this landmark law suit.
</P>
<P>
One of them said that they will take a more active part in
wildlife protection but also take better care of their cows.
</P>
<P>
Yang Shihe, the secretary-general of the Jilin Wildlife
Protection Association, says that the fact that the special
compensation case was dealt with so rationally probably will have
a positive impact on wildlife protection.
</P>
<P>
Wu Songlin, the mayor of Jiaohe where the incident occurred,
explains that the government paid 70 percent of the farmers' loss,
in accordance with national and provincial law.
</P>
<P>
He said the case shows farmers' increased awareness of the law
and the need for environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Since August of 1997, at least 12 cows have been eaten by wild
tigers in the Changbai Mountains.  
</P>
</TEXT>
