<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traders Imitating Their Successful Ancestors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Standing in the gateway of his
restaurant, Mao Guowei greeted his guests warmly. Just like his
successful ancestors, Mao is capable and good at trading.
</P>
<P>
He quit his job a few years ago with a government department
and opened the restaurant in the ancient city of Pingyao in north
China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
"The reputation of my ancestors does me a favor in business,"
said Mao, recalling one of his ancestors, Mao Honghui, who opened
China's first bank 170 years ago.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the 19th century, Mao's ancestors and their
fellow villagers built a financial network across the country, and
they even had businesses in Russia, Mongolia, Japan and Korea. At
that time, Pingyao and neighboring regions developed into a "Wall
Street" of Far East.
</P>
<P>
"Though my ancestors were quite rich, they left us little,"
said Mao, explaining that most bankers and traders declared
bankruptcy upon the invasion of foreign forces in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
Impoverished and without resources, the descendants of veteran
financial tycoons led hard lives in local dark cave dwellings for
nearly half a century.
</P>
<P>
"Things have changed so much today," murmured Mao, gazing from
the balcony of his new apartment at a group of cave dwellings
close to collapse in the distance. He and his family left the
caves about 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Like Mao, most local residents today engage in business, and
some of them have become China's major coal producers. Latest
reports show that the assets of non-state-run industrial
enterprises is responsible for 50 percent of the region's industry.
</P>
<P>
As offsprings of successful traders, they took trading for
granted. However, during the Cultural Revolution (1966-1976) when
the market economy was strictly banned, they could support their
families only with small salaries or by relying on relief.
</P>
<P>
"We enjoy today's prosperity and freedom," said Mao, who can
earn more than 100,000 yuan (12,000 U.S. dollars) each year.
</P>
<P>
In the daytime, Mao and his wife take good care of their
restaurant; at night, the couple say they prefer to relax by
watching performances or chatting.
</P>
<P>
Local government also have worked out favorable policies to
promote the local economy and develop tourism.
</P>
<P>
In the southern part of the city are many larger, old-style
houses, each with a beautiful yard, which hint at the luxurious
lives of their owners a century ago -- grand banquets, dazzling
jewelry, beautiful dresses, and coming and going in carriages and
cars.
</P>
<P>
City residents redecorated these houses in accordance with
their original styles and sold items left by their ancestors,
including antiques, paintings and old-fashioned furnitures,
drawing large numbers of overseas tourists. Several state-run
banks were quite busy with daily exchange.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the ancient city of Pingyao was added to the World
Cultural Heritage List. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
