<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Registers Big Trade Surplus in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- France registered a 15.41 billion
francs (2.56 billion U.S. dollars) trade surplus in April, up from
12.58 billion francs (2.1 billion U.S.dollars) in March, said the
French Customs on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Export stood at 148.74 billion francs (24.79 billion
U.S.dollars), while import accounted for 133.34 billion francs
(22.23 billion U.S.dollars).
</P>
<P>
France's trade surplus with the 11 countries which will join
the European single currency next January stood at 1.86 billion
francs (311 million U.S. dollars) in April, compared with 1.26
billion francs (210 million U.S. dollars) in March.
</P>
<P>
However, France registered a total of 56.82 billion francs
(9.47 billion U.S.dollars) trade surplus from January to April
this year, up from 46.440 billion francs (7.74 billion
U.S. dollars) in the same period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Asian Companies Increase Web Site Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Seventy-five percent of the
largest 1,000 companies in Asia have established a presence on the
World Wide Web of the Internet, said the International Development
Corp.(IDC).
</P>
<P>
IDC, the leading U.S. provider of information technology data,
analysis and consulting, said in a new report Friday that this is
up from 57 percent since October 1997 when the firm conducted the
first-ever study of Asian corporate Web site adoption.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, approximately 81 percent of the U.S. companies
with at least 100 employees have established Web sites, according
to IDC.
</P>
<P>
"In just eight months there has been an 18 percent increase in
the number of Web sites created by large corporations in Asia,"
said the IDC report. "The importance of the Internet as a business
tool is rapidly gaining wide acceptance in Asia's corporate
culture, Asia's Web sites have entered a new phase of maturity."
</P>
<P>
Asia's information technology vendors should be encouraged by
the findings, said IDC. Asia's Internet service providers have
recently experienced increasing costs and decreasing income due to
equipment and backbone access fees being charged in U.S. dollars
and subscriber income trickling through in troubled local
currencies.
</P>
<P>
The IDC survey also looked for the ability to complete business
transit through the Web site as well as the quality of Asian Web
sites in terms of layout, navigation, download speeds, ease of
navigation and accessibility. "All areas showed improvement over
the eight month study gap," IDC said.
</P>
<P>
Corporate Web sites in Asia are now showing company financial
information, providing online customer support and using online
registration facilities, according to IDC.
</P>
<P>
IDC believes that the top 1,000 companies in Asia which are
ranked by sales revenues would increasingly use the Web as a
medium for marketing communications and this offers significant
opportunity to vendors of Internet-related products and services.
</P>
