<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Algerian singer Matoub Lounes, who is a symbol of the
culture of the Berber people, was killed by gunman on
Thursday. The assassination, which came on the eve of the
entering into force of a law on imposing the Arabic as the only
language in Algeria on July 5, risked to trigger violence in the
Kabylia region, where the Berber language is used.
</P>
<P>
-- French President Jacques Chirac said on Thursday in Namibia
that France is ready to provide technology in cattle rearing,
fishing, agricultural and food industry, transport and energy to
southern African countries. Chirac and his Namibian counterpart
Sam Nujoma also laid the first stone of a new Franco-Namibian
cultural center in Windhoek.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The European Court of Justice cancelled on Thursday a
decision by the European Commission to allow the French
government to provide Air France with a 20 billion franc (3.3
billion U.S. dollars) aid package. The court ruling came after
seven European air companies, including three British air
companies, presented a complaint on the commission's
authorization. The British Airways said that the ruling means
that the future of European air companies lies in the land of
free enterprises instead of the pocket of tax-payers.
</P>
<P>
-- The Algerian singer Matoub Lounes was killed and his wife
injured in an attack on their car in a village in Kabylia on
Thursday. Hated by Islamists and censored by the government,
Matoub had his name added to a list of assassinated artists in
Algeria. 
</P>
