<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Cite Vegetables as Top Money-earner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Most Chinese farmers believe
growing vegetables can bring them the most money, a national
survey shows.
</P>
<P>
More than 67 percent of farmers responding to a national survey
conducted by the State Information Center said they prefer to grow
vegetables because they are the most economically efficient.
</P>
<P>
The second preferred production of Chinese farmers is growing
fruit, followed by grain and cotton, the survey indicates.
</P>
<P>
Geographically speaking, farmers of Beijing and Shanxi Province
have the largest proportion of vegetable-lovers, accounting for
84.88 and 86.11 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Hainan Province has the biggest group of fruit-growing
advocates, accounting for 66.13 percent.
</P>
<P>
The major grain-producing province of Heilongjiang in northeast
China has 58 percent of its farmers selecting grain as the first
production choice.
</P>
<P>
China's leading cotton grower, the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, boasts 64.06 percent of farmers citing cotton as the
priority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
