<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese State Company Trying Multiple Ownerships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A subsidiary of Wuhan Iron and Steel
Corp. was recently given the status of an independent legal
person, a sign that multiple ownerships will be sought to improve
the debt-ridden state sector.
</P>
<P>
The Powder Metallurgical Company, which was a wholly
state-owned enterprise, has been transformed into a stock
cooperative with the parent company holding controlling shares and
workers buying into it.
</P>
<P>
Another 18 of the steel company's state-owned enterprises will
follow suit, allowing non-government sectors to participate in the
reform. "We will encourage different forms of capital operation
methods in the process, such as shareholders' congress, stock
cooperation, merger, combination, and sales," said the steel
company's general manager, Liu Benren.
</P>
<P>
One of China's steel giants, Wuhan Iron and Steel Corp. began
to trim its payrolls in 1992, and has relocated 120,000 workers,
70,000 of whom have been organized to work in non-steel
businesses. However, the lack of independent legal person's status
had greatly limited the sector's further development.
</P>
<P>
Adoption of multiple ownerships will breathe new life into the
reform of state-owned enterprises, Liu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
