<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Golf Course Construction Called Excessive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Rolling green golf courses are
picturesque and entertaining, but they eat up too much precious
arable land, experts here claim.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the State Bureau of Land
Administration, China has completed the construction of 58 golf
courses covering 12,266 hectares of land, of which 3,800 hectares
are arable land.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 60 golf courses are under construction and 16 more
courses will be built, which are expected to occupy another 8,000
hectares of arable land.
</P>
<P>
The per-capita arable land in China is 0.066 hectare, one of
the lowest in the world.
</P>
<P>
The golf course projects are mainly located in coastal
developed areas, where the shortage of arable land is more severe.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that with a huge population and inadequate arable
land, China is a country not suited for building a large number of
golf courses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Destroys Confiscated Narcotic Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AYUTTHAYA (THAILAND), June 26 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's central
province Ayutthaya Thursday destroyed 632.6 kilograms of seized
narcotic drugs at an incinerator in the province.
</P>
<P>
Anti-drug officials said the involvement of an incinerator
reflected the increasing environmental consciousness of the
Narcotics Control Division of the Public Health Ministry, which
has been conducting such destruction of drugs since 1977.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Bhichai Rattakul attended the destruction
ceremony in Ayutthaya, more than 70 kilometers north of the
capital of Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister said the destruction, two weeks after
the special session of the United Nations on narcotics, showed the
Thai government's commitment to controlling the use and
trafficking of illicit drugs.
</P>
<P>
Northern Thailand was once part of the infamous "Golden
Triangle", one of the world's major opium producing areas. After
some 20 years of efforts, Thailand has almost eliminated opium
poppy cultivation in its territory.
</P>
<P>
The narcotic drugs burnt Thursday were seized in connection
with 268 cases throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The drugs included 208.1 kilograms of heroin, 170.6 kilograms
of opium, 25.1 kilograms of methamphetamine, 7.75 kilograms of
marijuana, 0.94 kilograms of ephedrine and 0.14 kilograms of
Kratom leaf confiscated by the Public Health Ministry, and 219.9
kilograms of marijuana seized by the Office of Narcotics Board and
the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's drug burning ceremony is the 21st of its kind since
1977. Narcotic drugs destroyed in such ceremonies from 1977 to
1997 amounted to 33,130 kilograms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
