<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Visits Village in Outskirts of Xi'an </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and his
wife Hillary visited a village, about one kilometer away from the
site of the unearthed terra-cotta warriors, in the outskirts of
the ancient city of Xi'an, northwest China, here this morning.
</P>
<P>
The Xiahe village with a population of more than 1,300 people
has become affluent thanks to its service to tourists who come to
see the thousands of life-size terra-cotta warriors unearthed in
the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The terra-cotta warriors dating back over 2,000 years in Qin
Dynasty (221-207 BC) in China's history were discovered by local
farmers in 1974 when digging a well.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent of their income comes from businesses or
tourism.
</P>
<P>
At ten o'clock this morning, the Clintons came to the Xiahe
Village and were greeted by the village head Yang Yunlong,
villagers and school children.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton and his wife Hillary talked for some 40
minutes with six villagers under a tree, and among the villagers
are a farmer, a primary school teacher, a restaurant manager and a
college student.
</P>
<P>
Focusing on the topic of "China's Changes and I", the villagers
answered questions raised by Clinton and his wife.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a brief speech at the village primary school,
Clinton said he had learned that local farmers have employed
advanced farming techniques so they can spend more time on
traveling, on making arts and crafts and other trades.
</P>
<P>
He said he was pleased to see that the villagers now have TV
and telephone sets and a primary school, and the life of the
villagers has been improved like those in other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Clinton wished the village a brighter future.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the villagers, village head Yang Yunlong extended
warm welcome to the US president and his wife and delegation,
saying that "The president's current visit will help further the
friendship between the people of the two countries."
</P>
<P>
Two primary school children presented bouquets of fresh flowers
to President and Mrs Clinton, who in turn waved the flowers to the
pupils and villagers in acknowledgement.
</P>
<P>
At the end of Clinton's speech, a group of pupils offered a
song entitled "Songs and Smiles". Clinton shook hands with each of
the pupils while Hillary clapped her hands along with the rhythm
of the music.
</P>
<P>
"Please take my song back to your home town, please leave your
smiles here," the children sang their send-off to the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
While the couple was shown around the village, the village life
was as usual: senior villagers sat at their doors of their houses
and some were doing their business while kids were running around,
playing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
