<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Cases Decrease in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The HIV infection in Uganda has
dropped from 13 to 9.5 percent between 1994 and 1997 as a result
of increased HIV/AIDS awareness.
</P>
<P>
The report, issued here Thursday on a live satellite talk on
AIDS and behavioral change, attributed the drop to Uganda's
efforts to sensitize the general public on the dangers of
the epidemic and the proper protection.
</P>
<P>
It said polygamy especially in developing countries is
held mainly responsible for the spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The talk, teleconferenced live from Washington by a panel of
three specialists on AIDS policy in the United States, was aimed
at sensitizing people on how to adopt safer sex practices as a
preventive measure to AIDS infection.
</P>
<P>
The report reiterated that abstinence, sticking to one partner
and use of the condom remain the best method in checking AIDS
prevalence.
</P>
<P>
The experts advocated for women's economic empowerment to
enable them to negotiate for safer sex with their male
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the high HIV/AIDS rate in Africa is a
result of poverty and mass migration due to armed conflicts on
the continent.
</P>
<P>
Out of 31 million people worldwide who are infected with HIV
and AIDS, 70 percent are in sub-Sahara Africa. In Uganda, 10
percent of its 20-million population are HIV positive and some
500,000 people have died of AIDS since the first case was
reported in 1982.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
