<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Players Predict Tough Match Against Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- German players are now thinking of
their next match against runners-up Mexico of Group E and predict
the match a tough one.
</P>
<P>
After finishing the winners of Group F, German captain Jurgen
Klinsmann said:"It makes no difference whether we play against
Holland or Mexico in the last 16. From now on every team has an
equal chance to win. Personally, I wouldn't have minded playing
against the Dutch because we've always beaten them."
</P>
<P>
Forward Oliver Bierhoff said:"We played a lot of high balls, but
it didn't work for us in the first half. Iran gained confidence and
had some dangerous scoring opportunities."
</P>
<P>
"Our team is playing better and better. We've shown that we're
unified and play well together," said Bierhoff, "We are pleased that
we won't play against Holland. The Mexicans are supposed to be a
good team, but we must be able to beat any team if we want to be
world champions."
</P>
<P>
German goal-keeper Andreas Kopke, who let in two goals in the
match against Yugoslavia, said:"We've accomplished our goal of not
playing against Holland. No team is easy to play against at this
point in the competition. We have a difficult game coming up
against Mexico."
</P>
<P>
Lothar Matthaus, who made World Cup history by playing his 23rd
game in the World Cup finals, said:"We are glad we're not playing
against Holland. We wanted to avoid them at all cost. We have to
watch out for Mexico, but I think we can beat them." 
</P>
