<HEADLINE> UNFPA Finances Uganda's Population Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kampala, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Population
Fund (UNFPA) has donated two million U.S. Dollars to Uganda to
facilitate advocacy programs in its population policy.
</P>
<P>
The money will be used to target health, population and gender
issues, all contributing to the country's population policy,
Director of Uganda's Population Secretariat, Jotham Musinguzi,
was quoted by Friday's New Vision newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Advocacy is a major sub-program to build alliances between
all the components which support population activities," he said.
</P>
<P>
Director of the UNFPA's technical and political department,
Mohamed Nizamuddin, commended Uganda on its progress in
implementing population and development initiatives.
</P>
<P>
The amount of money is small but it shows Uganda's commitment
to its population policy, he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official said that the money will help the Ugandan
government to coordinate other activities in agriculture, economy
and politics because population is not only about family planning
but it is a broader issue which needs support at different
levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
