<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: The Great Hall of the People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Great Hall of the People, an
imposing structure on the west of the vast Tian'anmen Square, will
be the venue for the summit meeting between Chinese President
Jiang Zemin and visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Built in ten months in 1959 with a total building floor space
of 171,800 sq. m., the Great Hall of the People is the meeting
place for the National People's Congress (NPC), China's supreme
legislature, and its standing committee.
</P>
<P>
Its main gate faces the Square to the east, propped up by 12
25-m-high light-grey marble columns and with a huge national
emblem adorning the lintel.
</P>
<P>
The central hall is just inside the main gate, behind which is
a 76 x 60 m. conference hall able to seat 10,000 people. On the
north of the Hall is a banquet hall able to seat 5,000 people,
while the southern wing is offices of the NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
The Hall also has smaller rooms named after China's provinces,
municipalities and autonomous regions and decorated in their
respective local styles.
</P>
<P>
The Hall was designed by Zhao Dongri and Shen Qi, former chief
architects of the Beijing Architectural Designing Institute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Bankers' Strike Called off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A proposed Kenyan bankers' strike
set for Friday has been called off and more than 12,000 bank
workers quited their union in a row over slowdown action to back
their claim for tax-free loans.
</P>
<P>
The walk-out leaves just 3,000 bank workers still in the giant
Kenya Union of Commercial Food and Allied Workers (KUCFAW) which
represents more than 50 member organizations countrywide, local
press reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The quited, represented by the All Banks Shopstewards
Committee, have accused the union of colluding with the
government to undermine their claim.
</P>
<P>
"We have today severed links with our trade union after they
deserted us in our proposal to go on strike," said Jacob Opiyo,
chairman of the shopstewards committee on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said the bankers have resolved to put the planned strike
"temporarily on hold", waiting further discussions among
representatives from the banking industry.
</P>
<P>
However, the bankers from all the 53 banks in the east African
country will fight until the tax on their low-interest loans is
removed, he vowed.
</P>
<P>
"We will never compromise on this offensive and punitive tax
and shall stop at nothing until the government scraps taxes on
our low-interest staff loans," he said.
</P>
<P>
The proposed free benefit tax sparked off a strike in February
among employees of the banks, forcing the government to
temporarily withdraw it.
</P>
<P>
Opiyo said if the tax proposals were implemented, members of
the bank will lose all the properties they had secured using the
loans because they can no longer service it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Increase Investment in Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government will
increase its investments in agriculture by a big margin this year,
the People's Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
However, the paper did not give an exact investment figure.
</P>
<P>
The increased investment will be used to build water
conservation, agricultural, forestry and poverty-elimination
projects, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the country plans to increase its input in
agriculture from other channels for building irrigation
facilities, harnessing rivers and speeding up farmland capital
construction.
</P>
<P>
China is a traditional agricultural state. Though its annual
grain output has risen to 500 billion kilograms, agriculture still
remains a weak link in the country, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
The country suffers from a loss of farmland to other uses, low
yields and a lack of irrigation systems. All these elements curb
the growth of agriculture and the national economy as a whole, the
paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0245 </DOCNO>
