<HEADLINE> College Sets Up Silk Institute in Jiangsu Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Suzhou University, based in east
China's Jiangsu Province, has just set up an institute to foster
professionals in silkworm raising and silk manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Suzhou is China's largest silk producer, with its annual output
accounting for one-sixth of the country's total. Local people
began planting mulberry trees and raising silkworms 4,700 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
In 1903, Shi Liangcai opened the country's first
silkworm-raising school in Shanghai. In 1911, the school was moved
to Xushuguan, Suzhou. Its name changed many times before it merged
with the Bio-Technology Institute of Suzhou University in 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to university sources, the newly established
institute has seven specialities with 20 professors and associate
professors and nearly 600 students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
