<HEADLINE> World Bank to Finances Four Development Projects in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) agreed here
Thursday to provide 348.8 million U.S. dollars for four
development projects in four African countries.
</P>
<P>
The first loan of 150 million dollars goes to Algeria's
low-income housing project to help improve living conditions in
selected urban slums and other areas.
</P>
<P>
The second interest-free credit, about 180 million dollars, is
earmarked for one of Cameroon's structural adjustment project.
</P>
<P>
The project will focus on consolidating and deepening reforms
in four areas: transport sector, privatization program for public
utilities and agro-industries, the financial sector and the
forestry sector.
</P>
<P>
This project will help increase employment and reduce poverty,
thus lay the groundwork for a substantial economic growth forestry
sector.
</P>
<P>
The third interest-free credit of some 12 million dollars is
provided to Cote d'Ivoire to help the country achieve a
sustainable growth rate of at least 6 percent per year through
increased levels of investments and exports.
</P>
<P>
Another credit of 6.8 million dollars will be used to assist
Lesotho's agricultural policy and capacity building project.
</P>
<P>
This project will improve institutional and policy arrangements
for the sustainable and efficient management, financing and
delivery of public and private agricultural services in Lesotho.
</P>
</TEXT>
