<HEADLINE> Guilin Mayor Foresees Stronger Economic, Trade Links with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Mayor of south China's Guilin city
Cai Yonglun said here today the people of the well-known tourist
attraction are expecting the visit by United States President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Cai told Xinhua that his city has a longstanding history of
economic and trade relations with the U.S..
</P>
<P>
President Clinton arrived in Xi'an in northwest China's Shaanxi
province at the first leg of a nine-day state visit to China on
Thursday evening. He will proceed to visit Beijing, Shanghai,
Guilin and Hong Kong. Xi'an, Beijing, Guilin are among the six
most popular tourist destinations in China.
</P>
<P>
Guilin, long renowned for its elegant rolling limestone hills
mirrored by limpid waters, has drawn 23 US-funded enterprises to
settle there.
</P>
<P>
Pepsi, the first U.S. firm to invest in the picturistic city in
1990, has built a 5-million-US-dollar production base in Guilin
to serve south China markets. In 1997, the Guilin Pepsi company
registered a 67 percent increase in sales revenue over the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Trade and economic relations between Guilin and the U.S. has
entered a new phase of growth since the forging of diplomatic ties
between China and the U.S. in 1979, he said, and total U.S.
investment in the city has reached 52 million US dollars at
present.
</P>
<P>
The largest Sino-US joint venture in the city is a pneumatic
tools factory with a total investment of 10 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Guilin has tourist industry as its main industry. Meanwhile, it
conducts trade with more than 50 countries and regions around the
world, and the U.S. is its second largest trade partner.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, two-way trade volume between the city and the U.S.
side reached approximately 27 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The city, with more than 35 percent of its land covered by
forests or woods, has increasingly been improving investment
environment by local efforts to strengthen its air, rail, road and
waterway transport and telecommunications links with the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
Cai said that Guilin, which has established sisterly ties with
the city of Orlando of the State of Florida, U.S., welcomes more
American investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
