<HEADLINE> Vietnam Calls for Anti-Drug Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam called on administrative
authorities at all levels and localities to help put an end to
drug trafficking and abuse, the Vietnam News Agency reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The call was made at a meeting by the Ministry of Health and
the United Nations' Drug Control Program in Hanoi to mark the
International Anti-Drug Day on June 26.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government is planning to allocate more funds
for the national program on drug control, which has achieved some
initial results since it was implemented four years ago.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in the 1993-97 period, 17,104 drug
trafficking incidents had been detected, while 7,255 kilograms of
opium, 170.8 kilograms of heroin, 11,234 kilograms of hashish, 242
kilograms of methamphetamine, 2.4 kilograms of codeine and a
million doses of other drug substances were confiscated.
</P>
<P>
There are about 130,000 drug addicts nationwide, with young
people under 30 accounting for 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
Worse still, the report said, illicit drugs have found their
way into educational establishments with thousands of school
students reportedly detected to be addicted to narcotics. 
</P>
