<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Foreign Investment Dominates Oil, Gas Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has been undertaking joint
exploration and production of crude oil and natural gas with a
number of foreign companies in its effort to increase the sector's
output to meet the domestic demand as well as to boost the export.
</P>
<P>
Up to the end of February this year, investments in the sector
from companies of Australia, Britain, France, Indonesia, Japan,
Malaysia, Thailand and the United States amounted to nearly 2.3
billion U.S. dollars in 45 related projects, forming the largest
chunk of the country's 7 billion dollar total foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Of the country's seven onshore and five offshore areas, the
Yadana gas field, made up of three blocks in the Gulf of Mottama,
has been explored and developed on a profit-sharing basis by a
foreign oil group comprising France's TOTAL, the United States'
UNOCAL, Thailand's PTTEP and the state-run Myanmar Oil and Gas
Enterprise (MOGE).
</P>
<P>
With the completion of the 674-kilometer pipeline (Myanmar
section for 414 km) running from the Yadana field to Thailand's
Ratchaburi, natural gas produced from the field is due to be
exported to Thailand beginning later this year at a rate of 522
million cubic feet (14.78 million cubic-meters) per day under a
30-year contract initiated between the Petroleum Authority of
Thailand and the developers in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
Another Myanmar's offshore natural gas field, the Yedagun off
the Tanintharyi coast constituted with another four blocks, has
also been explored and being developed by another foreign oil
group made up of the U.S. Texaco, Britain's Premier, Japan's
Nippon, Thailand's PTTEP and Myanmar's MOGE since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The Yedagun gas is also set to be sold to Thailand beginning
1999 according to another 30-year contract reached between the
Petroleum Authority of Thailand and the developers in March last
year.
</P>
<P>
The export target of the Yedagun gas, which was originally set
at 200 million cubic feet (5.6 million cubic meters) per day, is
to be increased to 400 million cubic feet (11.3 million cubic
meters) per day by the year 2000 by drilling some more test
wells, according to a recent official report.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the two oil groups, the Atlantic Richfield
company (ARCO) of the U.S. has also been drilling for oil and gas
at two test wells, the Shwepyihtay and the Shwepyiaye, off the
Mottama coast. Of these, the Shwepyihtay well has been yielding
gas on a commercial scale since March last year.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's Genting Sanyen and Dataran Isibumi are also
conducting activities in other six offshore blocks.
</P>
<P>
Foreign companies engaged in the extraction of oil and gas at
onshore areas in central Myanmar include Indonesia's APN and PT
Exspan Sumatra in Chauk, Yenangyaung, Ohndwe, Kyaukkyi-Mindon and
Padaukpin-Moenatgon areas.
</P>
<P>
Other foreign companies took up oil fields of Mann, Mindegyi
Chaungtha, Htaukshabin, Indaw and Myanaung.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the foreign investment in the crude oil and natural
gas, the sector's output grew by 37.7 percent in the 1997-98
fiscal year ending March with the crude oil production increasing
to 6.1 million barrels from 3.8 million barrels in the 1996-97 and
the natural gas output rising to 68,540 million cubic feet (1,940
million cubic meters) from 58,579 million cubic feet (1,658
million cubic meters) in the previous year, according to the
latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show that the country's economy achieved a
growth rate of 4.6 percent in the 1997-98 fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Missing in Traffic Accident in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Five people were missing and
another seriously injured Thursday when a van plunged into the
Bhote Koshi river in Sindhupalchok district of central Nepal,
Radio Nepal said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The injured was found on the bank of the river, and the police
and the local people were searching for the missing, the state-run
radio said, quoting the district police office.
</P>
<P>
The police are investigating into the cause of the accident, it
added.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, a bus plunged into the Marsyangdi river in Tanahun
district of western Nepal, and 40 of its passengers are still
missing. 
</P>
