<HEADLINE> Clinton Impressed by China's Rapid Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. President Bill
Clinton said here today that he was amazed by the
rapid economic growth China has scored in the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
In a 40-minute discussion with six local residents this morning
at Xiahe Village in the suburbs of Xi'an, the first stop of
Clinton's nine-day state visit, the president said, "It's very
impressive how much economic progress has been made in such a
short period of time."
</P>
<P>
Talking with a woman who sponsored a home for the aged, Clinton
said the question of caring the old is "the biggest issue" in the
world.
</P>
<P>
He also asked a villager about what has contributed to the
sharp increase of their income.
</P>
<P>
Yang Dongyi, a 56-year-old self-employed businessman, replied
that it was because the government adopted a good policy and the
people have the freedom to do what they are good at.
</P>
<P>
China started its reform and opening-up drive two decades ago.
</P>
