<HEADLINE> Russian-Ukrainian Talks On Military Trust "Unprecedented" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's Vice Foreign Minister
Vladimir Handogy said Thursday that the first round of
negotiations on measures of building military trust in the Black
Sea region was "unprecedented".
</P>
<P>
A communique following the talks on Tuesday and Wednesday said
that the adoption and implementation of these measures would
support economic cooperations between the littoral countries of
the Black Sea and strengthen security, peace and stability in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The measures will not be directed against any third country, it
added.
</P>
<P>
Handogy told reporters that until today there was no such
international document which served as a guideline for military
activities on the sea.
</P>
<P>
Though no final document was reached in the negotiations, the
countries agreed the document, if approved, will have politically
compulsory force, he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the parties concerned have agreed on the agenda
of the second round negotiations scheduled for October 6 in
Vienna, where they will decide on the scope of military trust
measures and the forms of military activities on the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of Ukraine, Russia, Turkey, Bulgaria, Romania
and Georgia attended the two-day talks in Kiev.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Ukraine proposed that the littoral countries of the
Black Sea draw up measures on strengthening military trust on the
sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
