<HEADLINE> Clinton Comes to Increase Sino-US Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- "I come to China to increase the
ties between our two nations," US President Bill Clinton said this
morning when he was visiting a village in the outskirts of the
ancient city of Xi'an, northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a group of villagers and school children in the
village primary school, the visiting US president wished "a
brighter future" for the Xiahe village, which is about one km away
from the terra-cotta museum.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that he has got to know that the village will soon
elect its leaders as the villages in other parts of China do, and
he added this will bring an even brighter future for the villagers.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the villagers now have TV and telephone sets apart
from their own school, Clinton said that life of the villagers has
improved remarkably in this village as in other rural areas in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of advanced farming technology has enabled the
villagers to pursue other trades such as tourism and manufacturing
such as 12 village businesses, he added.
</P>
<P>
The visiting US president and his wife Hillary and delegation
were accorded a warm welcome from the village head Yang
Yunlong and his fellow villagers and school children.
</P>
<P>
"The President's visit will help enhance the friendship between
the people of the two countries," Yang said.
</P>
<P>
Two pupils presented bouquets of fresh flowers to the Clintons,
who waved the flowers to the villagers in acknowledgement. 
</P>
