<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Muslims Gather on Day of Jumah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- At 1:30 in the afternoon, more
than 300 Muslims of China's Hui nationality who were dressed in
white hats gathered in the 7-meter-high Tongxin Mosque, knelt on
the carpet in rows and piously prayed toward the west.
</P>
<P>
Today, on the day of Jumah, Zhou Xuehai, a 57-year-old Hui
farmer in northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, as
usual, came to the Tongxin Mosque half an hour in advance from his
home five kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
He first went to the bathroom next to the main hall and took a
shower. Then he put on his white hat and entered the hall to pray.
</P>
<P>
"As I am a Muslim, attending the gathering on the day of Jumah
is compulsory," he said.
</P>
<P>
Like the 1 billion Muslims worldwide, about 20 million Muslims
in China also are holding gatherings in the country's 36,000
mosques.
</P>
<P>
Since China started its reform and opening-up, the policy on
freedom of religious belief has been revived and all religious
sites reopened. The country has also built new mosques.
</P>
<P>
The Tongxin Mosque, dating back more than 600 years, has been
put under the special protection of the autonomous region. There
is one mosque for each 500 Muslims in Tongxin County.
</P>
<P>
"I have attended the gathering on the day of Jumah for more
than 10 years," said Zhou, who is now running a cashmere business
in addition to farming. With an increase in the living standard,
he now goes to the mosque by motorcycle, instead of on foot.
</P>
<P>
At the same time people are gathering at the Tongxin Mosque,
prayers can be heard from the nearby Beida Mosque, only three
kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
"Each Muslim enjoys the freedom of religious belief in China,"
said Ma Xuefu, director in charge of the Beida Mosque.
</P>
<P>
In Ningxia, China's largest residence for people of the Hui
nationality, 1.78 million Muslims are celebrating their day of
Jumah in more than 3,000 mosques. Tongxin, a county with the
largest population of Hui nationality in China, has 15 mosques
that belong to four different Islamic sections.
</P>
<P>
Ma Quanyou, a 52-year-old farmer of Hui nationality, said the
Muslims attending today's gathering in the Beida Mosque come from
three different religious sections.
</P>
<P>
"Each Islamic section reads the same Koran and worships the
same Allah. The only difference lies in the religious rites," he
said.
</P>
<P>
To show respect to Muslims of different Islamic sections, the
Beida Mosque has a curtain hung in the prayer hall. Muslims of
different sections can pray in their own way behind the curtain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Signs Revised Bailout Agreement With IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
signed a revised bailout agreement with the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) to arrest the country's economic crisis, according to
local press reports Friday.
</P>
<P>
The revised agreement, the fourth in nine months, was signed by
Coordinating Minister of Economy, Finance and Industry Ginandjar
Kartasasmita and IMF Asia-Pacific Director Hubert Neiss here
Wednesday night and was announced Thursday after a meeting between
President B.J. Habibie and Neiss.
</P>
<P>
Compared with last April's agreement, the IMF has revised
downward its macroeconomic forecasts for the country as a result
of the recent political crisis that led to the resignation of
former president Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
Under the new agreement, the rupiah is expected to strengthen
to 10,000 per dollar by the end of 1998, against about 15,000
currently; inflation is projected to top 80 percent; the country's
economy is projected to contract by more than 10 percent and the
budget deficit is to be 8.5 percent of gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
A report quoted analysts as saying that the new forecasts are
too rosy. They believed that the inflation rate might even reach
three digits if the situation did not improve, and the rupiah
target of 10,000 is optimistic.
</P>
<P>
The new agreement also allows the Indonesian government to
maintain subsidies on food, fuel, electricity and other spending
to help the poor cope with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Previously, the IMF insisted these subsidies be phased out
within the year.
</P>
<P>
The revised agreement calls for further support of the
international community to ensure the success of the IMF's
economic program.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank announced in Manila Thursday that it
would extend 1.5 billion U.S. dollars in new loans to Indonesia.
The World Bank has already pledged 1 billion dollars and Japan is
also expected to come up with more aid next month.
</P>
<P>
"Rebuilding the economy is for the Indonesian people alone to
do. But this endeavor is difficult without the help from the
international community, given the extent of the problem,"
Ginandjar said.
</P>
<P>
The revised agreement paves the way for the resumption of the
43-billion-dollar IMF-led rescue package. It was reported that the
IMF Executive Board will decide on the disbursement of the second
tranche of 3 billion U.S. dollars in loan in the middle of next
month.
</P>
<P>
The disbursement of the second tranche, supposed to be
channeled in stages in May, June and July, was delayed due to
riots in Jakarta in May and the political crisis in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
