<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean metallurgical exports amounted to 290
million U.S. dollars during the January-April period of this year,
a 10.7 percent increase over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The exports to the South Common Market reduced by 15.5 percent
to 130 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Merida power plant in eastern Mexico
received a 173.5 million dollar credit jointly granted by the
United States, Japan and the Hermes Group of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The plant will generate 484 megawatts of electricity and use
natural gas as the primary fuel.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The Argentine firm Industrias Metalurgicas
Pescarmona S.A. won a bidding of 450 million dollars for the
construction of a power plant in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned National Power Corporation is the entity in
charge of the project, which also includes the rehabilitation of
two other plants in the phase of construction in the south of
Luzon Island in the Asian country.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The gross value of the Brazilian agriculture and
livestock production is expected to reach 55.1 billion dollars
this year, a 3.2 percent increase over 1997.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 55.1 billion dollars, 35.2 billion dollars came from
agriculture production and 19.9 billion dollars from the livestock
sector.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The Nicaraguan government, the Economic Commission
of the National Assembly and the Association of Private Banks of
Nicaragua agreed to give the green light to the approval of a loan
from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank will grant a 70 million dollar credit to support
the Nicaraguan reform of its financial system.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The United States Commerce and Development
Agency provided a 195,000 dollar loan to the Latin American
Aviation Commission for a project of geodesic technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
The project, involving 19 airports in Latin American countries,
will promote the establishment of satellite navigation and make
aviation safer in Central and South America.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuela agreed to reduce its oil output by an
additional 200,000 barrels a day during the meeting of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) held in
Vienna.
</P>
<P>
OPEC agreed to cut production by 1.38 million barrels per day,
a figure that surpasses the first round of cuts agreed on in
March, or 1.245 million barrels a day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
