<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Violence Against Women Increases in Ecuador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Violence against women in Ecuador
has increased 166.6 percent in the last four years, according to
the Center for Studies and Research on Woman in Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
The situation has become a social and economic problem for the
country, a local press report said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Last year, there were 27,000 reported cases of abuse and
maltreatment to women, while 14,000 cases were documented in the
first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-seven percent of the women experienced physical and
psychological maltreatment, while 13 percent, most of them minors,
go to police precincts to report sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
The women's center attributes the increase of reports to the
fact that more victims report their cases now, where they once
preferred to remain silent.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from the country's Human Rights
Ecumenical Commission, most of the women abused or offended come
from low income families or situations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
