<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Step Up National Drug Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 26 (Xinhua) -- China will increase its efforts on
drug control and strengthen cooperation with international
organizations and other countries to combat cross-border drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily quoted an official with the Ministry of
Public Security as saying that a defense force composed of
police, militaries, Customs officers, militiamen and border
residents will be set up in the southwest border area, which is
adjacent to the "Golden Triangle" drug source.
</P>
<P>
This is among a series of steps to block the channels for drug
trafficking through China. The patrol are also meant to keep drugs
out of the country, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Drug growing, processing and trafficking outside China's
southwest border has become increasingly serious.
</P>
<P>
According to James Sasser, US Ambassador to China, the United
States and China are to open drug enforcement offices in each
other's capitals to transmit information and co-ordinate
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Incomplete statistics given by the Narcotics Control Office
indicate that between 1991 and 1997, 413,423 drug-related criminal
cases were solved and 309,116 people involved were arrested across
the country.
</P>
<P>
Also during that period, 26.88 tons of heroin, 14.48 tons of
opium, 5.63 tons of amphetamine and 10.8 tons of marijuana were
confiscated, the statistics show.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, China had 540,000 registered drug addicts,
more than 80 percent of whom are younger than 35.
</P>
<P>
But even official sources acknowledge that the actual number
could be much higher.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
