<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Percent GDP Growth Predicted for Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines could still achieve
a 3 percent growth in gross domestic product (GDP) this year and a
5 percent increase in 1999, the Philippine Daily Inquirer said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Cayetano Paderanga, forecaster of the Pacific
Economic Cooperation Council for the Philippines, as saying that
despite the slowdown of the economy in the first quarter, the
country's GDP could grow by 3 percent this year and probably 5
percent next year.
</P>
<P>
He said that there is "a very good chance" that the country's
average inflation rate for this year would be contained at 9
percent despite the disappointing 10.3 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
Investment growth in the country would drastically decelerate
to 2.4 percent this year from 10 percent last year because of a
tight monetary policy, he said.
</P>
<P>
Taking into consideration the recent data, Paderanga said, he
has revised his export growth forecast from 9 percent this year
and 11 percent next year to 15 percent for both years.
</P>
<P>
He said that he has likewise changed his import growth
projection for this year from 7 percent to 2 percent and for next
year from 9 percent to 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
As the country's GDP growth was registered at only 2.5 percent
in the first quarter, the government this week revised the growth
target for the whole year from 3-4 percent to 2.5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
