<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Pregnancy Rate Drops in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- A report released by a
government agency Thursday says that the teen pregnancy rate is
down across the United States.
</P>
<P>
The report said that falling teen birth rates cannot be
attributed to an increase in abortions. In fact, in every state
that reports data, fewer teens are getting pregnant in the first
place, said the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention under
the Department of Health and Human Service.
</P>
<P>
Officials cite less sex and greater use of birth control as the
major reasons. Others suggest an improved economy may be giving
teens more hope for the future and more motivation to avoid
getting pregnant.
</P>
<P>
Still, nearly one million teen-age girls become pregnant each
year, and more than 200,000 girls have abortions.
</P>
<P>
Previous reports found that teen birth rates and teen sexual
activity both dropped by 1995.
</P>
<P>
"The early 1990s were a turning point in adolescent pregnancy
trends, following the increase that occurred in the 1980s," said
Donna Shalala, secretary of the Department of Health and Human
Services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Banks' Foreign Debts Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Due to the continued weakening of
the peso against the U.S. dollar, the foreign exchange liabilities
of the Philippine commercial banking industry increased to 532
billion pesos (13.4 billion U.S. dollars) in April, according to
the latest figures provided by the Central Bank of the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that the banks' foreign debts in April were 156
billion pesos (3.7 billion dollars) higher than in the same month
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The increase in foreign debts was mainly due to the
depreciation of the country's currency against the dollar, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Since a regional financial crisis hit the country last July,
the Philippine currency has depreciated by more than 30 percent
against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the central bank, in dollar terms, the
foreign debts of the country's commercial banks had actually gone
down to 13.4 billion dollars as of April from 14.2 billion dollars
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Bank sources said that the commercial banks had been reducing
their foreign debts following the drop in import requirements in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The commercial banks had also been trying to pay their maturing
foreign exchange obligations, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
But their net foreign exchange liabilities still amounted to
8.1 billion dollars, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
