<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Internet Economy to Nearly Quadruple by 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Internet-related spending of
businesses and consumers will hit 124 billion U.S. dollars this
year and over half a trillion dollars in 2002, according to a
research paper.
</P>
<P>
The Massachusetts-based International Data Corporation (IDC)
said in its latest research report that in just four short years,
100 million Americans are expected to get access to the Web on a
regular basis.
</P>
<P>
The report received here on Thursday said:
</P>
<P>
-- By 2002 U.S. businesses will spend over 200 billion dollars
on Internet technology deployment, or 20 percent of all spending
on technology. By the end of 1998, that spending will reach over
62 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- The availability of venture capital to invest in Internet
companies will nearly double this year to over 8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- Total purchase of goods and services over Internet in the
U.S. will close in on 250 billion dollars in 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
