<HEADLINE> Chicago Bulls Start to Search for Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- With the NBA draft over, the
Chicago Bulls start to search a replacement for coach Phil
Jackson, who left the sixth-time champion team Monday.
</P>
<P>
But it looks very difficult to find someone who is able to win
the hearts and trust of Michael Jordan, Scottie Pippen and Dennis
Rodman.
</P>
<P>
"We'll do it slowly, we'll do it surely and we'll do our
homework," Bulls general manager Jerry Krause said last night.
"We'll do what we have to do."
</P>
<P>
Krause said he and chairman Jerry Reinsdorf know what they're
looking for, and they have a solid number of people they want to
talk to about the job.
</P>
<P>
The general manager said the Bulls want to hire someone within
the next few weeks, and they prefer to hire a coach who can sign a
long-term contract.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, Pippen and Rodman will be free agents this summer, and
whether they remain in the team could depend on who will coach
them.
</P>
<P>
"We're going to try and get this team back," Krause said. "We
lost a good coach, but we are interesting in bringing this team
back." 
</P>
