<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Opposes U.N. Debate on Israel's Jerusalem Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Thursday that it would oppose a Security Council debate on
Israel's plans for Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said Bahrain, the only Arab country on the
15-member Security Council currently, had informed the council
it was preparing a draft resolution on Israel's plan to expand
Jerusalem municipal services to Jewish settlements in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain said Arab ambassadors to the United Nations wanted an
open debate on the issue, meaning that non-council members could
participate.
</P>
<P>
But State Department spokesman James Rubin said the proposed
Security Council debate on Israel's plan for Jerusalem would be
counterproductive and unhelpful to the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Security Council discussion of this issue would be unhelpful
to the peace process. Any action in the Security Council would
be counterproductive to the success of our discussions with the
Palestinians and the Israelis," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It might feel good to engate in such an exercise at the
United Nations, but it will do bad to the peace process," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Rubin also opposed to enhance the status of the Palestinian
mission to the United Nations as Arab countries proposed. He
said giving the Palestinian mission more rights would amount to
"unilateral action" by the Arabs, undermining U.S. attempts to
prevent Israel's own unilateral actions.
</P>
<P>
"We oppose enhanced status for the PLO(Palestine Liberation
Organization) in the General Assembly. The PLO is not a state
and should not enjoy rights tantamount to those of a state," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The status of the Palestinian mission is expected to come up
on July 7, when the General Assembly considers its request for
almost the same rights as a member state, a U.N. spokesman said
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But Rubin said the request by the Palestinians would
"constitute exactly the kind of unilateral action that we have
asked both parties to avoid, and would therefore, undercut our
efforts to get Israel to refrain from such acts as well."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
