<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Soldier's Body Back Home From Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The remains of Israeli soldier
Itamar Ilya, killed last September in a botched commando raid in
south Lebanon, was brought back to Israel via a French airplane on
Thursday, Israel radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The return of Ilya is part of a deal worked out between
Israel, Lebanese militant group Hezbollah and the Lebanese
government after months of tough negotiations mediated by both the
French government and the International Committee of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
Ilya's body was transported to Lod military airport in central
Israel. Once the body has been positively identified, the French
plane will fly back to Beirut with the remains of 40 Hezbollah
fighters killed in clashes in south Lebanon with Israeli troops
and its allied South Lebanon Army militia.
</P>
<P>
Among the bodies will be that of Hadi Nasrallah, son of
Hezbollah leader Sheikh Hassan Nasrallah.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 60 Hezbollah activists being held in Israeli
prison, will be released Friday as the last stage of the deal.
</P>
<P>
Ilya was killed in last September, when his commando squad was
ambushed by Hezbollah guerrillas in south Lebanon. Israeli
helicopters failed to bring back his remains from the field.
</P>
<P>
The swap was the first exchange of its kind since July 1996,
when Hezbollah returned the remains of two Israeli soldiers held
since 1986 in exchange for 126 guerrillas under a German-brokered
deal.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a self-styled "security zone" in south
Lebanon in 1985 after two invasions, with the claimed aim to
protect its northern border from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Shiite Muslim militant Hezbollah is the most
active guerrilla group fighting to oust Israeli troops and its
allied Lebanese militiamen from the area.
</P>
<P>
Despite the swap deal, confrontation between Israel and
Hezbollah continued. In the latest incident Thursday morning, two
Israeli soldiers were killed by road-side bombs in south
Lebanon. Hezbollah has claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Israel is locked up in a war of attrition in south Lebanon,
from where it now wants to pull its troops out, but with
preconditions. The United Nations Security Council resolution 425,
adopted two decades ago, calls for "immediate and unconditional"
Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
