<HEADLINE> Germany Says "No" to Kosovo Independence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 25 (Xinhua) -- German leaders Thursday made it clear
to visiting Kosovo-Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova that Bonn will
only support autonomy for the Serbian province of Kosovo, not an
independent state.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Rugova in Bonn Thursday afternoon, Kohl
expressed deep worry about escalation of violence in Kosovo as
well as sufferings of civilians, German government spokesman Otto
Hauser said.
</P>
<P>
While noting that Belgrade should take the main responsibility
for the worsening situation, Kohl made an urgent call on
Kosovo-Albanians to make their own contributions to ending
bloodshed and refugee outflows.
</P>
<P>
"What is necessary is a clear commitment to non-violence, to a
peace dialogue with Belgrade with international participation and
to a negotiated solution for Kosovo on the basis of a broad
autonomy within the territories of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia," the spokesman quoted Kohl as saying.
</P>
<P>
Similar view was also voiced by German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel earlier Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot support anything but autonomy for Kosovo.... The
ethnic Albanians should not cherish any illusion about an
independent state," Kinkel said after his talks with Rugova
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have been running high in Kosovo since February, when
Serbian police clashed with ethnic Albanians seeking independence
from Belgrade and integration into neighboring Albania.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, Yugoslavia has stripped autonomy of the
ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the province's
population.
</P>
<P>
As he did Wednesday in Brussels, Rugova Thursday again pleaded
in Bonn for "an independent and neutral Kosovo" as well as "an
international protectorate" status for the region in what he
described as a transitional step to full independence.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the world community to intervene in order to
halt Serbian attacks in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The political dialogue with Belgrade could only be resumed
after such attacks had been stopped, Rugova said.
</P>
<P>
While not ruling out a possible outside military intervention,
Kohl stressed that international pressure on Belgrade was only
plausible if the whole Kosovo-Albanian leadership made
unconditional commitment to the non-violence approach and pledged
to stop the violent activities by armed ethnic Albanian rebels.
</P>
<P>
According to Western press reports, Rugova, who backs
negotiation for independence, is rapidly losing popular support to
Kosovo rebels who are fighting for independence but whose
leadership and structure are little known.
</P>
<P>
Rugova, however, pledged in Bonn that he would make efforts to
contact the rebel groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
