<HEADLINE> Belgium for Lifting Sanctions Against Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Belgium favors lifting the
sanctions imposed on Burundi by regional states after the July
1996 coup that brought Pierre Buyoya to power, the U.N.
Humanitarian Information Unit IRIN said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian Foreign Minister told Belgian radio that it was
time "to pay a little attention to the fate of the (Burundi)
population, which is currently dramatic," an IRIN press release
said.
</P>
<P>
A senior Belgian diplomat told IRIN Thursday that Belgium
believed Buyoya's government deserved some recognition for taking
"important steps" and demonstrating "seriousness" in both the
internal and Arusha peace processes.
</P>
<P>
Before the peace talks by Burundi's 17 parties held in Arusha,
Tanzania earlier this month, Buyoya named an official of one of
the Hutu factions as vice president of the country and agreed to
attend the talks which resulted in agreeing, last Sunday, to a
truce as from July 20 in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The issue of sanctions and a possible summit of regional heads
of state to review them was not officially mentioned in Sunday's
declaration of the 17-party talks, and seems unlikely before the
next round of talks set for July 20, analysts said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Besides, European Commissioner Joao de Deus Pinheiro also said
Tuesday that the EU was intending to gradually resume its
cooperation with Burundi, according to an EU press release quoted
by the IRIN report.
</P>
<P>
Pinheiro, the commissioner responsible for development,
cooperation and external relations with the ACP countries, met
Tuesday with Speaker of the Burundi parliament Leonce
Ngendakumana, who briefed him on recent political progress in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Pinheiro declared that the EU would start by relaunching
rehabilitation as well as returnee and displaced peoples'
resettlement activities. New resources could be made available as
progress is made in the peace process, Pinheiro was quoted as
saying. 
</P>
