<HEADLINE> Egypt's Nile Islands to Become Natural Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 25 (Xinhua) -- The dozens of Egyptian islands lying
on the river Nile will be preserved as natural reserves, according
to a decision made by Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ganzouri said in press statements that the governorates in
which these islands are situated should treat them in accordance
with the Environment Law.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Cabinet and Follow-up Affairs Talaat Ahmed Hammad
said there are about 144 permanent islands in the course of the
Nile in addition to about 216 seasonal islands, which appear and
disappear depending on the level of Nile water. Total area of the
permanent islands is 36,861 feddans (15,481.62 hectares).
</P>
<P>
The decision to preserve these islands as natural reserves was
issued in compliance with the law for the protection of the Nile
in 1982.
</P>
<P>
The 6,700-kilometer-long Nile, the world's second longest river
and Africa's longest, runs 1,530 kilometers across Egypt
south-north before pouring into the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
With a deficient rainfall over the entire country, human
existence in Egypt depends closely on irrigation from the Nile,
resulting in the acute concentration of nearly 98 percent of all
Egyptians in the Nile Valley (only 4 percent of Egypt's area).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
