<HEADLINE> Queen Opens New British Library </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Queen Elizabeth officially opened
the new British Library in London on Thursday following 36 years
of work.
</P>
<P>
She said: "I have now toured this remarkable building, and to
my mind it is truly worthy of our country's contribution to
literature and scholarship, to science and technology; a
contribution which has been, and still is, second to none."
</P>
<P>
The 520 million pound (870 million U.S. dollars) library,
housed in a red brick building near London's St Pancras railway
station, is one of Britain's most expensive public buildings this
century.
</P>
<P>
It contains 20 million books and documents, including two of
the four copies of the Magna Carta and the only surviving
manuscript of "Beowulf."
</P>
<P>
The project was first mooted after World War Two and design
work started 22 years ago. But it was dogged by delays, rising
costs and technical problems and will not be fully operational
until 1999.
</P>
<P>
In the new library, it takes only 30 minutes to retrieve books
from underground shelves instead of an average two-hour wait in
the old premises.  
</P>
