<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah, Israel Exchange Corpses of Dead Fighters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's Hezbollah (Party of God)
and Israel Thursday exchanged their fighters' corpses held by each
other under the auspices of the International Committee for the
Red Cross (ICRC).
</P>
<P>
A French military plane took the mutilated remains of Israeli
sergeant Itamar Ilya from the Beirut International Airport to Tel
Aviv via Cyprus and returned later with 40 bodies of Lebanese
guerrillas killed in attacks in the Israeli occupied south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of Lebanese guerrillas included 28 from Hezbollah,
nine from Lebanon's another anti-Israeli Muslim group Amal led by
House Speaker Nabih Berri and three from Lebanese Communist
Party.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony at the airport to welcome the arrival of
the 40 dead bodies, Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri said that
it's the first time since Israeli occupation of south Lebanon
began that the Lebanese government assumes the sole role in the
name of Lebanon for conducting the negotiations on the swap of
fighters' corpses with Israel.
</P>
<P>
He called those Lebanese fighters "the country's heroes,"
saying they gave their lives to safeguard their nation's right to
live in freedom and dignity.
</P>
<P>
The honor guards stood in formation to welcome the remains of
the fighters. Outside the airport, thousands of Muslim people
have been waiting for more than two hours, banners with
black-and-yellow Hezbollah insignia in their hands.
</P>
<P>
Ilya was one of the 12 Israeli soldiers killed in a bungled
commando raid in a southern Lebanese village of Insariyeh last
September.
</P>
<P>
His remains which Israeli helicopter failed to pick up from
the battle field were jointly held by Hezbollah and Amal.
</P>
<P>
The part of Ilya's scalp Amal is holding is not included in the
exchange as the group disagreed with Israel over the number and
names of Lebanese prisoners to be released from Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah sources said the exchange operation came after nine
months of tortuous negotiations between the two parties and they
credited the success of the exchange to the great efforts the ICRC
has played in coordination with the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
They described the swap, the second between Hezbollah and
Israel in two years, as a "great victory" for the country's
resistance movement, Lebanese people and the nation's unity.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its northern
settlements from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's anti-occupation movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has never stopped military resistance against Israel's
2,000 troops in south Lebanon and incurred heavy losses on them.
</P>
<P>
The swap for the return of Ilya's remains will also include the
release of 60 Lebanese prisoners, 10 from Israeli jails and the
other 50 from Khiam prison in south Lebanon run by Israeli allied
militia South Lebanese Army.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to be freed and sent home by the ICRC through
the Kfar Falous crossing that links the enclave to the rest of
Lebanon on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
