<HEADLINE> UN Under-Secretary-General Reports Humanitarian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 25 (Xinhua) -- As a result of the civil
war in Burundi, over a million Burundians or approximately one
sixth of the country's population now live outside their homes, U.N.
Under-Secretary-General for Humanitarian Affairs Sergio Vieira de
Mello told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mello, who has just paid a visit to Burundi, said with nearly
670,000 people living in over 300 camps within its borders,
Burundi hosts the largest internally displaced population in the
Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
Mello said the five western-most provinces, which are
chronically unstable due to recurrent rebel activity and military
operations, hold over seventy percent of the country's
displaced population.
</P>
<P>
He said Burundi has also produced the highest number of
refugees in the region, with nearly 300,000 people living in the
neighboring countries of Tanzania, the Democratic Republic of
the Congo and Rwanda, and Tanzania is the host to the largest
number of Burundi refugees and has paid a high price in terms of
environmental damage and exacerbated tension with its neighbor.
</P>
<P>
Mello predicted that the situation is unlikely to improve in
the near future, as continued instability prevents the majority
of the affected population from returning to their homes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
