<HEADLINE> N.Irish Terrorist Jailed 25 years for Bombing in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- A Irish Republic Army's terrorist
was jailed for 25 years on Thursday for his part in a bomb blast
that killed two people and devastated buildings in Docklands in
east London.
</P>
<P>
James McCardel, 29, of Crossmaglen, Co Armagh in Northern
Ireland, was found guilty on Wednesday of conspiring to cause
explosions by the Woolwich Crown Court jury.
</P>
<P>
It was McCardle's second trial for the explosion, which caused
damage estimated at 150 million pounds (250 million U.S. dollars).
The first jury was discharged in February after failing to reach a
verdict.
</P>
<P>
It was announced later on Thursday that there would be no
retrial and the murder charges would remain on the file.
</P>
<P>
A co-defendant, Patrick McKinley, was cleared during the first
trial on the judge's direction of conspiring to cause explosions.
</P>
</TEXT>
