<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US House Committee Approves China's MFN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 25 (Xinhua) -- As U.S. President Bill Clinton
is on a nine-day visit to China, a powerful committee of the House
of Representatives voted Thursday to back his decision to renew
China's most-favored nation (MFN) trading status.
</P>
<P>
The Ways and Means Committee decided by voice to support the
president's June 3 decision on the renewal of China's MFN for
another year and urged fellow lawmakers to reject attempts to
sever normal trade relations with that Asian country.
</P>
<P>
The vote took place following a short debate on a resolution
that would overturn the president's decision. The committee
recommended to the full House of Representatives that lawmakers
vote against the resolution and support normal trade with China.
</P>
<P>
The committee took the step hours after President Clinton
arrived in Xi'an, China's historical capital and the first stop of
the president's current trip. Clinton said at a welcoming ceremony
that "There may be those here and back in America who wonder
whether closer ties and deeper friendship between America and
China are good. Clearly, the answer is yes."
</P>
<P>
Committee Chairman Bill Archer, a Texas Republican, said:"I am
opposed to this resolution because it essentially would terminate
U.S. trade relations With China, and extinguish our ability to
improve the human rights situation there."
</P>
<P>
Opponents argued that the United States should suspend normal
trade relations with China until that Asian country improve its
record on human rights, forced abortions, religious persecutions
and proliferation.
</P>
<P>
However, Archer and many others believed that MFN does not give
China any special trade privileges but continues a trade status
that has been extended to almost every other country in the world.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that denying normal trade relations with China
would be counterproductive and unlikely to achieve what the
opponents want.
</P>
<P>
Philip Crane, an Illinois Republican, said:"As one of the
world's oldest and most influential civilizations, China will not
respond to shrill threats from Congress to extinguish trade."
</P>
<P>
Congress is investigating the alleged transfer of sensitive
missile technology to China by a U.S. company that launched
satellites atop Chinese rockets and illegal Chinese campaign
contributions to Democrats in 1996. China and the American company
have denied any wrongdoings and demanded the continuation of
normal trade relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Newt Gingrich, a Georgia Republican, is among the
first group of lawmakers who came up to support the president soon
after he made his decision public three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
"There are no practical grounds for cutting off American
producers, American agriculture, American companies," Gingrich
said. "I would argue that if you believe in democracy it is better
to have Americans in China doing business than it is to cut the
Chinese off from contact with the American people."
</P>
<P>
Congress has 90 days to endorse or overturn the president's
decision. Some predict that MFN will be accorded to China at last,
but it might be more difficult to achieve this year because of the
ongoing Congress investigation.
</P>
<P>
However the powerful speaker, critical of the president on many
issues, told a press conference that "it will pass and I think we
may have a better vote than people expect."
</P>
<P>
It is believed that revoking China's MFN would hurt both
because tariff on goods imported from China would soar to an
average 40 percent from a current level of about 6 percent and
prices would rise.
</P>
<P>
The United States is China's second largest trading partner and
China is America's fourth largest. Their trade volume totaled 72
billion U.S. dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton told his Chinese hosts in Xi'an that "We have
a powerful ability to help each other grow. We can learn much from
each other. And as two great nations, we have a special
responsibility to the future of the world." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980626.0349 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Qualify for Second Round in World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTPELLIER, June 25 (Xinhua) -- Powerhouse Germany reached the
second round of the soccer World Cup finals after beating Iran 2-0 in
their last group F game here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Germany opened the scoring through Olivier Bierhoff, who headed
home a pass from Thomas Hassler five minutes into the second half.
</P>
<P>
Captain Jurgen Klinsmann showed his killer instinct in front of the
Iranian goal seven minutes later but this time Bierhoff was also
involved.
</P>
<P>
Bierhoff, who plays in Italian club Udinese, blasted a powerful
shot against the left-hand post. The ball rebounded towards Tottenham
Hotspur striker Klinsmann, who surged ahead to head it home.
</P>
<P>
Bierhoff almost made it 3-0 for Germany in the 60th minute but his
shot went wide past right post.
</P>
<P>
Iran's best chance came midway through the second half, when a shot
from Mehdi Mahdavikia was saved by German keeper Andreas Kopke.
</P>
<P>
The Iranians, who apparently wanted to play a game mainly based on
fast counter-attacks, were helpless through the first half before a
strong German defence.
</P>
<P>
After trailing two goals behind, Iran began to attack more
aggressively and had several chances in the front, but their strikers
lacked enough finishing power to materialize them.
</P>
<P>
Germany, who finished atop the group, would face group E runners-up
Mexico in the second round in Montpellier on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia also qualified by placing second in the group after
beating the United states 1-0 in another match on Thursday. They will
face group E winners the Netherlands in Toulouse also on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
